The Prague stock exchange was in the red by the end of trading
The Prague stock exchange corrected its losses after the sharp fall in the morning.
Transactions with the shares of the Czech Energy Company (ČEZ) reached almost half of the usual daily trading.
The Prague stock market continued its Monday decline right from the start of trading on Tuesday, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the fall in Wall Street stocks is behind the decline.
Here, too, the market&#39;s reaction to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to support the stabilization plan for the financial sector there, is manifested in this way.
Shares fall in Asia
Stocks in Asia saw a dramatic fall on Tuesday, although indices eventually erased some of the losses later in the day.
Hong Kong&#39;s Hang Seng stock index lost almost four percent during trading, but later pared some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which monitors Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, and markets were closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but losses eventually narrowed to 4.3 percent.
The Taiwanese stock market fell 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
&quot;The timing of the US bailout is uncertain and will affect the world&#39;s financial markets,&quot; said Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Financial Council.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it determines its monetary policy independently, that is, independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, American lawmakers should immediately resume negotiations and accept the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a danger that other countries will also feel the consequences.
A bloodbath for US stocks
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the draft to support the financial system, for which 700 billion dollars (almost 12 trillion crowns) should have been spent.
In doing so, lawmakers ignored President George Bush&#39;s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the draft would solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
On Monday, American stocks experienced a bloodbath and the leading stock indexes registered the biggest drop in 20 years.
The Dow Jones fell by almost seven percent, the last time it experienced a similar decline was in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it became clear that the proposal was not accepted in the House of Representatives, the index began to free fall.
Congress backed down: The US government can thus pump 700 billion dollars into the banks
The top leaders of the US Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush agreed on the broader form of the agreement and the financial assistance to be provided to the US financial system.
This will be voted on early next week.
US lawmakers have reached a breakthrough in negotiations to approve the rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the US financial system in the amount of 700 billion dollars (about 12 trillion crowns).
But no victory yet.
Congress must finalize some details of the agreement before they can make public the final form of the law and their vote.
The support draft for the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the Financial Institutions Committee, informed the Reuters news agency about this on Sunday.
According to Senate sources, the draft will probably be voted on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, there should be an announcement that the bailout plan will be approved, which is the first important psychological factor in the revival of financial markets.
However, due to the complexity of the mechanisms, &quot;sobering&quot; takes place afterwards.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
&quot;We have taken a big step.
We have resolved our differing views on what the package should look like to stabilize the market,&quot; Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to him, the final vote can take place on Sunday.
Representatives of the legislators met with Henry Paulson, the US Treasury Secretary, on Saturday night to give a final form to the government fund.
This should buy the unsalable mortgage assets from the financial companies, which lead the financial companies to heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
&quot;We are close to final agreement on a design that will work and also be effective in the market.
There&#39;s still work to be done on the remedial plan, but I think we&#39;re there,&quot; Paulson said.
A signal to trade in Asia
The global financial crisis has a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Nevada Democratic Senator Harry Reid, the lawmakers are therefore trying to reach a final agreement in Congress on Sunday.
This is because they want to reassure investors before the start of trading on the Asian financial markets, where, due to the time zone, the decision of Congress could be the first to influence Monday&#39;s trading.
For now, however, it is not clear when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, nor is it clear whether the trial might get stuck at the last minute due to some problem.
Lawmakers hope to pass the law in the coming days.
However, the law is still undergoing many changes.
The total amount intended to help the system must be divided into two parts.
According to President George Bush&#39;s request, the first 350 billion dollars should be available as soon as possible.
But Congress can block the release of the remaining amount, set at another $100 billion and later at $350 billion, if it feels the program isn&#39;t doing its job.
Bush praised the progress in the negotiations
Although the president can veto this decision, Congress can override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program remained, which was to acquire financial assets for the purchase of bad mortgage securities that have lost their value, as hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgage loans.
&quot;We worked everything out.
The House should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday,&quot; Republican Sen. Judd Gregg said.
American President Bush is also satisfied with the progress achieved in the negotiations.
Bush spokesman Tony Fratto said the president was pleased with Saturday&#39;s progress and appreciated the &quot;bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.&quot;
Restrictions on severance pay
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, who led the negotiations, said lawmakers agreed on responsibility for the financial program, protecting taxpayers from losses, ending benefits, and the timing of the funding bill.
The new law requires directors participating in the program to also limits busás&#39;s severance pay and establishes a committee to supervise the fund.
The fund should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
&quot;We&#39;ve worked very hard on this, and we&#39;ve made great strides toward an agreement that will work and benefit all Americans,&quot; Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance to homeowners who are having trouble making repayments.
The government should negotiate new repayment installments for the mortgages it buys, with the aim of reducing debtors&#39; monthly repayments and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Spiritual help
According to David Marek, chief economist of Patria Finance, the proposed draft is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
&quot;All this is because it is impossible to know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets will be acquired.
This will determine how the financial sector and the government distribute the losses among themselves,&quot; Marek told iHNed.cz website this week.
According to Marek, it is not so important that the plan is approved now or at the beginning of next week.
&quot;It is much more important that Congress decide this week that they support the plan and give their blessing as soon as possible.
The spiritual importance of reaching an agreement that the plan will be approved is the most important thing at this moment,&quot; Marek emphasized.
Victory of right-wing populists in Austria, they have a total of 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, Austria&#39;s early parliamentary elections on Sunday brought about a perceptible weakening of the two parties of the grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
The Austrian People&#39;s Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, was seriously shaken, suffered a particularly strong loss.
On the other hand, Jörg Haider, president of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), regional leader of Carinthia, is preparing for a victorious return to national politics.
Based on the preliminary results, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the votes, but compared to the last elections in 2006, it lost 5.5 percent of the votes.
The ÖVP fared even worse, losing almost nine percent of the votes with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results achieved by both major parties in Austria&#39;s post-war history, and the result is literally catastrophic, especially for the People&#39;s Party, which called for early elections.
At the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People&#39;s Party had a significant advantage over the SPÖ, according to opinion polls.
However, the voters clearly punished him for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of Wilhelm Molterer, party president and current vice-chancellor.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party presidency.
This development would probably facilitate the increasingly likely way out of the election result, i.e. the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP grand coalition.
Given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Freedom Party of Austria (FPÖ) initially won 18 percent of the votes and the BZÖ 11 percent of the votes - however, the social democrats at the same time voiced their fear of a repeat of 1999, when the People&#39;s Party in a joint government agreed with the populists (the FPÖ was still united at the time, it separated from the BZÖ in 2005), which even caused sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with any party, and I assume that he can return to Vienna in national politics, is obviously counting on this solution.
The Green Party also made it to the parliament, but it lost some of its popularity and dropped from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties exceeded the four percent limit and did not enter the parliament.
Duel at the edge of the blade: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We&#39;ll help you choose
While almost all mobile phones can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
From this it seems clear that it is better to just buy a phone.
That being said, there are many reasons to get a dedicated MP3 player.
The choice depends entirely on the way of use and the needs of the future owner.
You probably have a hard time getting a top-of-the-line, expensive record player for your home to listen to the latest Maxim Turbulenc record on.
On the one hand, such musical products do not appear on vinyl records, but there is no objective reason for this in terms of quality either.
However, if your shelves are full of art rock, jazz or blues vinyl records, you probably dream of such a turntable.
This is similar to MP3 music intended for travel, that is, compressed - simplified.
There are also price and quality categories here.
It may be unacceptable for some to spend eight thousand kroner for a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan probably finds it difficult to accept a twenty kroner market earphone.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide.
Battery life also matters
Some of the top quality music players can do much more than just play music, but also do things that most mobiles don&#39;t even happen to be able to do.
No device today is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to the primary functions, calling and sending SMS, it can also play music and video, record both, has a better or worse camera, and can even navigate.
And if you consider smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
This is a bit of a miracle, since no refrigerator can grill and no television can take photos.
However, multi-functional mobile phones also have disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the more often the display sends it to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Few mobile devices can play music for more than ten or twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
With cheap mobile phones, therefore, expect that they won&#39;t play for you for more than a few hours.
If you also make calls here and there, get another charger for safety at work - this also applies to more expensive devices.
You won&#39;t have this problem with MP3 players, even the worse ones can last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
The next problem arises when uploading music to mobile.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be connected directly to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few card readers can cope with the miniature memory cards used in mobile phones without an adapter.
With a few exceptions (iPod), you don&#39;t need any special software for players.
It is enough to load the device with music from the computer via USB.
The majority of mobile phones and players already create their own music library sorted by the name of the artist, album, genre, or, for example, the user&#39;s rating.
Some devices only show a tree structure like Windows Explorer, and some know both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with OS).
Players are easier to handle, mobiles know more
When choosing a specific device, inquire primarily about battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output, and of course the comfort of use.
If you mainly use music as a background and you only listen to it for a short time a day, for example on the tram, any mobile phone that plays MP3 is suitable for you.
Any mobile phone can do this.
You don&#39;t even need to pay particular attention to what music formats your mobile or player supports.
Everyone can handle MP3, and the vast majority of the music you receive will be in this format.
MP3 is one of the most common, and the vast majority of devices also handle music in WMA format.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPod) is less common.
Better mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough to visit the respective pages of the service provider (or other service provider) and buy the song or album via the mobile Internet.
This service in itself can be a strong argument for purchasing a music mobile.
Unfortunately, the offer of the service providers is lousy and usually limited to only one year&#39;s radio hits.
The prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it can be assumed that this kind of way of selling music (whether via GSM, Internet, or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people keep their mobile devices with them all the time.
Whenever he feels like listening to something, he fumbles with his mobile phone in his pocket, while the forgotten MP3 player is lying around at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry the earphones or at least the speakerphone.
If not, you can use the built-in speaker, which almost all mobile phones have, but few MP3 players have.
For many, the biggest advantage of music mobiles will probably be the price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
Between three and four thousand crowns you can already get a pretty decent walkman.
However, you are mostly limited by the lack of a traditional headphone output.
The best and most technically equipped phones with traditional 3.5 mm hole earphones can cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
At the same time, the advantage of the players, among other things, is the simple handling.
The simplest - by no means necessarily the cheapest - players (see our selection) can really be handled by everyone.
Minimal functionality, handling similar to a conventional cassette recorder or gramophone is obvious.
There is no danger of a crash in the form of accidentally switching on the mobile internet, nor of the huge bill for data transfer that follows.
Which device should we choose?
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for replaceable memory cards (M2, microSD type, etc.).
With the purchase of the appropriate card, you can get a maximum of two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic types only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2GB.
Only the most expensive ones know what to do with memory cards of up to 8 GB.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, choose Cowon, Creative, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Based on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you don&#39;t have to spend more than 1,100 kroner.
If you belong to the more demanding listeners, choose special mobile walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices also have a separate MP3 control button, so the comfort of operation is similar to that of an MP3 player.
The furthest in the industry is Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series mobile phones have the same user interface as MP3 players sold separately.
MP3 players of the above-mentioned brands can provide the same service in the same price range up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, maximum 35 hours).
The first virtual service provider will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively developed and our service providers offer practically the same services as their Western European partners.
Nevertheless, we are missing something here - a virtual service provider forcing the classic service providers to significantly reduce their prices.
Maybe it won&#39;t be like that for much longer.
We have written many times on the Mobil.cz website that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This was also confirmed by ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of SMS in the Czech Republic is more expensive than in other EU countries.
After the European Commission&#39;s latest move to regulate roaming charges, this may lead to a controversial situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, text messages sent from abroad will be cheaper than domestic ones.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory, since we have three mobile networks and our penetration is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile service providers are happy to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvořák, the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority, often agrees with this, as he has stated several times before that there is no room for new service providers in the Czech Republic.
It is perhaps true that the classic service provider with its own network probably does not have much of a chance (however, it would probably be difficult to find a frequency).
However, there is another option - the virtual service provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market that brought about a significant price reduction, to which classic service providers also had to respond.
Meanwhile, even before the entry of big fish such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to ours were heard in Great Britain.
However, it has been proven that such providers have a place and can indeed be successful.
However, we don&#39;t have to go far for an example.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the Mobilking virtual service provider in Poland.
This service provider managed to acquire more than 100,000 customers in less than half a year and become the fifth largest service provider there.
Meanwhile, Mobilking is backed by the Penta financial group, which in the Czech Republic owns U:fon among others.
The advantage of virtual service providers is the ability to focus on a much narrower target group.
In order to operate effectively, you need far fewer customers than a traditional service provider.
It does not involve relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual service providers in the world are thus generally seen as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which, however, are often offset by fewer services.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers text messages at least fifty percent cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move to bet on a so-called target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
&quot;Real men choose the Mobilking service provider - who they like, who they can trust,&quot; says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to say whether an idea similar to the one in Poland can work here.
Miroslav Čepický, Vodafone&#39;s spokesperson, doubts this: &quot;The Czech market is relatively small for the segmented approach on which the majority of virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory in terms of the range of services.&quot;
There is no chance in the Czech Republic, the mobile service providers claim
However, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual service provider in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
&quot;We are talking about the successful expansion of this project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not seem very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will take place in other countries of our region,&quot; said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman of the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
This indirectly proved that the existing mobile service providers in the Czech Republic are not overly sympathetic to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything in their power to ensure that no potential competition can arise.
For some time now, the GTS Novera group has not been hiding its interest in launching a virtual service provider, thereby taking another step towards making Telefonica O2 a real competitor in the field of corporate customers.
&quot;We are very interested in being able to provide our customers with not only fixed but also mobile telecommunication services.
The sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile service providers.
We have already made progress in negotiations with some of them,&quot; says Pavel Kaidl, the group&#39;s spokesman.
Maybe better times are coming.
From unofficial information, it seems that we may be lucky with the first virtual service provider by the end of the year.
However, his birth is surrounded by an impenetrable wall of silence.
&quot;At this moment, we do not think that there is a place for a full-fledged virtual service provider on the Czech market.
The Czech market, unlike other markets, is very special.
Until now, we have not been contacted by a unique entity offering a complex and serious project in this field,&quot; Vlastimil Sršeň from Telefónica 02&#39;s press department told Mobil.cz.
Other service providers also refer to the special situation of the Czech market.
Martina Kemrová, T-Mobile&#39;s spokeswoman, exceptionally agrees with O2 and adds: &quot;So far, we have not registered any viable and mutually beneficial business projects that could be further based on.&quot;
And he added: &quot;It is unlikely that any virtual service providers will appear in the T-Mobile network until the end of the year.
At this moment, we should have a concrete agreement on our table to be able to think in such a short term.&quot;
Vodafone is turning its attention to fulfilling its own 3G license requirements.
Miroslav Čepický adds: &quot;We are open to negotiations with possible virtual service providers, primarily in the area of sharing costs and infrastructure.
We consider this to be the most rewarding from the customer&#39;s point of view.
Vodafone&#39;s main strategy in this area is to find partners to build shared networks for fast mobile internet.&quot;
Responsible offices - on the same page as service providers
The procedure of the mobile service providers is easy to understand, the entry of another service provider would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a drop in prices and thus a decrease in their profits.
So why facilitate the entry of such competition?
When something is important to service providers, they are able to cooperate, as evidenced by the tug-of-war surrounding the birth of U:fon.
The greatest pressure on ČTÚ was probably around the birth of the T-Mobile company U:fon.
This is evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ website.
But now U:fon comes in handy as an argument why we should not allow the entry of the virtual service provider.
Martina Kemrová added to this: &quot;The competitive environment of the mobile market was recently strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile service provider into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that the entry of another player into the market and its services would place high demands.&quot;
Considering this attitude of the mobile service providers, however, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory bodies is truly amazing.
In the meantime, it is not only the attitude of ČTÚ, which unfortunately - unlike Great Britain and other developed countries - does not have the right to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
Only the Economic Competition Authority is entitled to this.
However, the office has a typical approach to the whole problem.
&quot;The entry of the virtual service provider into the mobile market would only be possible after the contract between the mobile service provider and the virtual service provider on the rental of the necessary infrastructure is concluded.
So far, no such contracts have been concluded, as the range of possible interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the traditional service providers,&quot; said Kristián Chlapua, from the External Relations Department of the Economic Competition Office, in response to our question.
A statement formulated in this way from the representatives of the service providers would probably not surprise anyone.
However, from the office that should represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one can abuse their market position, this is more than strange.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: &quot;Abroad, where virtual service providers usually operate, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to the reduction of the price of mobile phone services.&quot;
However, it is probably not in the interests of ÚOHS to put pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the reduction of prices.
In this case, the striking harmony revealed by the reactions of the three mobile service providers is truly shocking.
The question, whether it is really just a coincidence, is almost self-explanatory.
Just like the completely identical gasoline prices at gas stations, they are probably just the result of chance and fierce competition.
&quot;The office did not discover any signs of anti-competitive proceedings in this case, so there is no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the service providers has a leading position, i.e. they do not have a proportionally greater responsibility for their market actions.
The telecommunications regulator probably also lacks the necessary tools to open the mobile market of virtual service providers,&quot; said Chalupa.
The presentation of the market leading position is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, based on which telecommunications is the only market from the point of view of economic competition.
Of course, no Czech service provider is in a leading position in such a market.
However, some legal experts offer a different approach - the creation of a virtual service provider always requires the approval of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - relatively logically - has a monopoly on its own network.
So it is necessarily dominant in a certain segment.
But even if we do not accept this argument, it should at least be a warning to ÚOHS that three mobile service providers act in a strikingly similar way.
Meanwhile, complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that they encounter very similar obstacles during negotiations with all service providers.
Shifting the responsibility to ČTÚ is a relatively common trick in telecommunications, with which ÚOHS takes its hands off the whole matter.
We have already encountered this in a few similar situations.
Unfortunately, in the text of the recently adopted telecommunications law, the extension of ČTÚ&#39;s powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications was not implemented, even though many experts hoped that the situation would improve.
The representatives of the ÚOHS should know this well, but they probably have different interests.
This works when no one is watching
In the meantime, the operation of some kind of pseudo-virtual service providers, of which many are already operating in the Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that issue their own mobile phone service price lists, which are, however, only partially public.
Because we are talking about companies dealing with multilevel marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only available to selected people.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer vis-à-vis the service provider, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As a priority customer, you will then receive special price offers (and other discounts).
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile service providers prohibit similar prepayment.
&quot;If the cases you are talking about were to arise, it would be a breach of contract terms, which we would deal with and which could lead to the termination of cooperation with the given company,&quot; answered Martina Kemrová to our question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that the news about this kind of activity would not have reached the responsible people of the mobile service providers.
Primarily, in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
Meanwhile, no service provider defends itself against such a procedure.
These companies make a significant profit from their activities, and unlike real virtual service providers, they are not particularly threatened by their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický warns of possible problems: &quot;The law allows for similar speculations, however, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they have to accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have full access to it like general customers of mobile service providers.&quot;
But ČTÚ should at least be surprised by this.
In addition, another question arises for the ÚOHS.
If mobile service providers turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why are they preventing the birth of a virtual service provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively strong powers to uncover this kind of activity, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the explanation of the service providers that they did not suspect anything of the sort and that their terms of trade forbid it.
When we will not be the most expensive
As it was already mentioned a few times in the text, the entry of virtual service providers into the mobile market brought about a perceptible drop in the price of services.
Meanwhile, in practically all countries where virtual service providers have been established, classic service providers have tried to more or less prevent their establishment.
The arguments they used were practically the same - too small, perhaps too satisfied market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, the regulatory bodies intervened precisely at these moments, which did not protect the interests of the mobile service providers, but of their customers.
Then, either through formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved the creation of the first virtual service provider, which others followed.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are handing the whole case to each other.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that unclear competences come in handy for them in these cases.
But let&#39;s not give up the fight.
If the background information is good and the virtual service provider really appears in our country soon, the Czech mobile market might start moving again.
If a service provider were to allow the creation of a virtual mobile service provider, the ÚOHS could hardly remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of additional interested parties.
And compared to the rest of Europe, we may no longer be more expensive to call.
There are four new versions of the new Czech national anthem.
Choose the best one
Listen to four arrangements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek ceremoniously presented Where is my country? new recordings of the national anthem.
The anthem was recorded by the orchestra of the National Theater led by Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - with male or female solo vocals, choir or instrumental.
Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka sing.
The authors of the modification of the anthem are Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček.
You can listen to all four versions on the iHNed.cz website.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national song one of the most beautiful anthems.
He previously told Czech Radio that he deliberately chose young singers with representative voices who are expressive and popular to sing the solo variations.
&quot;Right from the beginning, I tried to ensure clear diction, easy comprehensibility of the text, and harmony with both of them, and later with the band as well,&quot; he mentioned.
The Czech national anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
Where is my country? The song was first performed at the Rendi Theater in 1834 in Josef Kajetán&#39;s play Tyl Fidlovačka, supplemented by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously claimed it as their own.
And the first verse of the song became a natural part of the national anthem after the founding of Czechoslovakia in 1918.
Even after the establishment of the independent Czech Republic, it remained one of the seven state symbols.
