On Wednesday, the Prague transport company will also deliver with a chip card for the first time
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will enter the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passenger who will have an electronic coupon in his pocket instead of a paper line ticket gets on the subways, trams and buses.
The coupon can currently be obtained by approximately one hundred thousand people who have the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy 30-day, 90-day and annual coupons (which will be valid from January 1, 2009) and save them on their chip cards at the information centers and branches of the Transport Company in Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
The coupons can be purchased online from yesterday via the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than four hundred customers by the afternoon.
Those who start using internet trading can once and for all forget the ticket windows of metro stations, where they had to regularly stand in long lines for line tickets until now.
The coupon can be purchased online and saved on the Opencard card in one of the thirteen branches of the City Library.
&quot;At these places, passengers have a desk with trained servers available to them, who help those interested in online shopping and also save their purchased coupons on their card,&quot; said Martin Opatrný, the project&#39;s spokesperson.
In addition to the libraries, electronic coupons will also be able to be saved to Opencard in the self-service machines installed in some lobbies.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket agents and passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, IP Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
&quot;Currently there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year there should be eighty,&quot; Opatrný added.
The coupon is checked by a machine instead of the driver
It is easy to manage the machines that will start operating tomorrow.
All you have to do is insert the Opencard chip card and the previously paid coupon will automatically be saved.
Starting tomorrow, electronic coupons will be valid not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So, on the trains and bus lines around the city from 300 to 499, which mainly the residents of the districts of Central Bohemia travel to the capital.
&quot;On the trains included in Prague&#39;s integrated transport, the conductors were equipped with card readers, with the help of which they can also determine the zone validity of the coupons,&quot; Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization, which compiles the Prague public transport timetable, explained the check of line tickets.
In buses around the city, card readers are installed near the driver at the cash desk.
When boarding, the driver must not only show the chip card, but also place the Opencard in the designated place on the side of the cash register.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the coupons.
&quot;If, for example, the passenger needs to check the validity of the coupons, the easiest way is to ask the driver for this,&quot; added Drápal.
Passengers who do not travel by buses around the city and do not remember when their coupon expires can go to the self-service machines that save coupons to cards again.
Information about the validity of their documents appears here on the device&#39;s display.
The Sudetenland wanted a referendum from the USA
The Sudeten Germans requested the annexation of Šumava to the United States in 1945.
This is clear from the letter that is in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
It is said that in 1945 some groups of Sudeten Germans approached the President of the USA with this wish.
This can also be seen from a letter from a private archive, which is currently kept in the collection of the Scientific Library of South Bohemia.
In the letter, the Germans from Česky Krumlov ask the American president not to allow the return of the &quot;Šumava County&quot; to the Czech Republic, which was still occupied by Hitler under the Munich Agreement.
&quot;We interpreted the situation correctly and we really want to be sure of the words according to which the American troops are not coming to the German territories as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators,&quot; says the letter, signed with the words &quot;People who carry the fate of Šumava in their hearts.&quot;
Since annexation to Czechoslovakia can supposedly give the Sudeten Germans - in addition to the knowledge of the Czech national character - only hope for brutality, ruthlessness, lack of understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American president to take over the protectorate over Šumava &quot;now and forever &quot;.
&quot;We cannot believe that, regardless of the opinion of four million inhabitants, he would judge this territory as a foreign country for us, which oppresses and enrages the minority, and would contribute almost nothing to the victory of the Allies,&quot; the letter states.
The reason why the authors could not sign is said to be the fear of revenge by the &quot;Czech oppressors&quot;.
So, if the president of the USA allegedly doubts the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, it would be enough for him to hold a referendum in the county of Šumava on whether its residents wish to become part of the USA and live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the wording of the letter may appear somewhat naive with current knowledge of post-war history, some historians believe it accurately portrays the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at the time.
Even if the Czech Germans had a minimal idea that they would be evicted from the country, only a few of them recognized the possibility of this.
Some expected the United States and Great Britain to agree to some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Still others hoped to simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is confirmed by Gustav Chalupa, an Austrian journalist born in České Budějovice.
Chalupa served in the Baltic Sea as a German from Budějovice during the war.
When he was captured by the British at the end of the war and thrown into the Holštynsko prison camp, dozens of other Czech Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
&quot;They believed that when they return home, the Czech language will come in handy,&quot; said Chalupa.
According to him, none of the German prisoners living in Czechoslovakia before the war expected to be deported from the country based on the Beneš decrees.
