Questions after an accident: Are bus attendants illegal?
The law does not recognize them, they are not allowed on a long-distance bus
In connection with the tragic bus accident of the Student Agency company near Padua, Italy, the question arose as to whether the attendants and passengers could travel in the bus during the journey.
&quot;If we wanted to follow the law strictly and formally, the activity of the flight attendant would be in conflict with the law on transport activities,&quot; says Karel Hanzelka, a spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
Last week, a 22-year-old passenger was killed, possibly caused by the driver of a lorry crossing the path of the bus.
Unfortunately for her, at that moment she was sitting next to the driver, in the least safe place on the bus, even though there were two more seats reserved for her.
The bus may crash or brake suddenly at the moment when the attendant is serving coffee or offering a newspaper.
Whether the bus has a parking space according to the traffic permit plays a role.
If it is not homologated in the bus, passengers must sit.
The long-distance buses of the Student Agency do not have standing places; which was also confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by Radim Jančura, the director of the company.
&quot;We tried to find a solution to this with the ministry, and at first the movement of passengers was not allowed.
However, this was withdrawn, and we came to the conclusion that passengers can go to the toilet during the journey, as long as they have their own seat,&quot; he stated his position.
The law does not recognize the flight attendant
&quot;There is no clear legal definition of the role of a flight attendant - no legislation regulates this position.
However, the carrier is not prohibited by any law from providing the services.
The law on road traffic only recognizes the concept of vehicle attendant; it does not define your rights and obligations,&quot; spokesperson Hanzelka adds less clearly.
On the contrary, Josef Pokorný, director of the Ministry of Transport&#39;s road vehicle operation department, believes that the law adequately addresses the problem.
&quot;It depends on whether the bus has a parking space in its license.
And that&#39;s it,&quot; he says.
According to their distinction, buses can be urban, with standing places and a limited maximum speed, and intercity buses with standing places and a permitted higher speed, and long-distance buses without standing places and a permitted maximum speed, with seats with seat belts.
Like on an airplane, says the expert
Jaroslav Hořín, BESIP&#39;s traffic safety expert, does not see a fundamental problem in the movement of the attendants on board the bus.
&quot;During continuous progress, there is not much danger, the situation can be compared to service on an airplane.
Here, too, it is not certain when there is turbulence and the flight attendant could hit his head.&quot;
&quot;However, if the bus suddenly brakes, of course the laws of physics apply.
Just like in city buses or trams.
The safety of the flight attendants must be solved by the carrier with internal rules,&quot; he says, and he also believes that the problem has not been solved from the point of view of the law.
Jančura is ready to terminate services
The Student Agency is the only bus carrier that offers passenger services.
It employs two hundred flight attendants.
Even after the accident, the director does not consider their occupation to be risky.
&quot;However, as soon as I get the impression that the occupation of flight attendants is risky, I will terminate them.
Passengers can receive coffee and newspapers upon boarding.
It would also save costs,&quot; he says.
Alexej Litvin, director of Asiana, which operates a fraction of flights compared to Student Agency, justified the lack of flight attendants in its vehicles with safety interests.
&quot;We don&#39;t have flight attendants, we&#39;ve been against this from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in some kind of fatal injury,&quot; he told Týden.cz just a year ago.
An incredible tragedy happened
A young flight attendant from Pilsen, who had been working for the company for two years, died during a scheduled flight to Naples.
The Slovenian truck probably turned out of the stop lane without using a turn signal and blocked the path of the bus.
The bus driver tried to avoid it with a sudden maneuver, but the right front part of the bus hit him.
Jančura denies that the two seats reserved for the rest of the flight attendants were also sold.
&quot;These seats cannot be booked on long-distance flights, they are blocked.&quot;
The company wants to sue the truck driver.
By compensating the girl&#39;s family, the agency does not wait for the court&#39;s verdict, but also expects financial compensation from the guilty party.
A change in the law?
In the distant future
The amendment to the law, on which the Ministry of Transport&#39;s 30-person expert group has been working for more than a year, could clarify the movement of the attendants on board the bus.
&quot;However, the group did not reach any concrete results.
Buses not so much, rather the point system deals with the maximum permitted speed on the highway and the use of mobile phones while driving,&quot; says expert Hořín.
&quot;The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activities of the attendants to be something that would fundamentally threaten the safety of the passengers,&quot; concludes spokesperson Hanzelka, adding that the control of the safety of buses is the responsibility of the police and labor offices.
Czech judges in the battle for the seabed
He walks over to the wall-mounted electronic map showing Australia and the adjacent marine areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a point disappearing in the blue of the ocean.
&quot;The island belongs to Australia, along with the adjacent seabed.
The area, meanwhile, is as big as the continent itself,&quot; says Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the UN Division&#39;s 30-member team on ocean and maritime affairs.
His boss, Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, director of the division, monitors the explanation, which he sometimes adds to it.
Work force and enthusiasm reign here.
The seabed is rich in natural resources and hides a hitherto little-known world.
Crude oil, ore and other minerals can be found here, as well as hitherto unknown living organisms, which could, for example, be the key to the development of anti-cancer medicine.
Sea floor larger than land
Today, coastal states are intensively applying for new underwater territories.
They assert their rights according to the UN convention, which was agreed upon in Montego Bay, Jamaica, in 1982.
It is primarily the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends up to a few hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
Such a country has exclusive rights under the Convention to all resources of the continental shelf.
&quot;Simplified, we consider the continental shelf to be the part of the seabed and the layer lying below, which is the natural continuation of the land under the sea.
At the borders of the coastal sea, often two hundred nautical miles, the so-called it also extends beyond the border of the exclusive economic zone,&quot; explains Mikulka.
The application that the given country submits to the Committee for Designating the Outer Limits of the Continental Shelf must be supplemented with extensive scientific and technical documentation based on numerous costly researches and measurements.
This is the result of many years of preparatory work.
&quot;One of our tasks is to provide legal and professional-technical assistance to the committee.
So far, the committee has discussed five applications, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three mentioned countries have been successful,&quot; adds Mikulka.
The success of Australia, which was the first to significantly expand its underwater country, has recently caused a stir in the world.
But New Zealand also won - the area of the seabed awarded to it by the commission is about 1.6 million square kilometers, that is, six times larger than the country&#39;s territory.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in research.
The profits from the future use of the seabed, they hope, will be priceless.
Other countries are constantly submitting their applications.
They can do so within ten years from the moment of ratification of the &quot;Montego Bay Convention&quot;.
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor declared by the convention as the &quot;common heritage of mankind&quot; begins.
No country has an exclusive position here.
The right of extraction in this area is given by the international institution established by the convention.
&quot;However, the seabed is not Klondike&quot;, exaggerates director Mikulka, saying that &quot;some of its areas are legally clearly demarcated and their regime is fixed in a contract&quot;.
Czechs in the Pacific Ocean
Part of the seabed also belongs to the Czech Republic today.
It shares this with other countries of the former Eastern bloc in the framework of the joint &quot;Interoceanmetal&quot; organization.
Based on the convention, this organization received the so-called &quot;pioneer investor&quot; status.
It is authorized to produce in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area inspected by the investor is slightly larger than the former Czechoslovakia.
The sea floor is divided there, it is a kind of underwater copy of the Tatras.
&quot;This can be mined in a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area is a rich deposit of polymetallic ores containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese,&quot; mentions another lawyer, Hindu Pakshi Rajan.
Rober Sandev, Macedonian colleague of the division, presents another example of concretion.
