Dusseldorf&#39;s hopes rest on Frankfurt
The letter of the WestLB board of directors to the bank&#39;s employees is not lacking in big words.
&quot;The central capital market organization of the savings bank financial group&quot; could be created from the merger of the units of the Düsseldorf financial institution and Frankfurt&#39;s Deka-Bank, says the letter published on Monday.
WestLB would bring a permanently profitable &quot;competency block&quot; into such a business.
Such a relationship could give the decisive impetus to further mergers in the provincial banking sector.
This is the reading of when a board wants to prove its ability to act in difficult times.
After all, there is still enormous pressure on the precarious WestLB bank.
Not only from the EU Commission, but also from the Federal Financial Services Authority, which recently informed the state government of North Rhine-Westphalia that the deadline for finding a lasting solution is pressing.
For savings bank customers, however, a kind of relationship between Deka-Bank, famous for its investment funds, and WestLB has been a topic for quite some time - also on the Frankfurt side.
Franz Waas, the head of Deka-Bank, announced at the end of August, when presenting the half-year data, that the merger of the bank located on Mainzer Landstrasse and a provincial bank such as Helaba or WestLB does not make sense.
Nevertheless, Deka&#39;s board of directors, which is made up of representatives of one half of the provincial banks and the other half of the savings bank associations, instructed the board to continue negotiations with WestLB on joint business activities.
During this, the capital market business or certain parts of it may be discussed.
However, financial circles claim, the negotiations have only just begun.
With its 3,000 employees, Deka-Bank, one of the most important employers in the financial sector in Frankfurt, is not the first to be mentioned in connection with the consolidation of the savings bank sector.
For a moment in 2003, it looked like Deka-Bank would merge with Landesbank Rheinland-Pfalz and Helaba.
However, nothing came of this triple alliance.
As soon as the plans were made public, the Hessen provincial government spoke out against Helaba&#39;s interest.
After that, the other two banks did not find each other either.
Instead, the Landesbank Rheinland-Pfalz was transferred to the Stuttgart-based Landesbank Baden-Württemberg.
However, the idea of a relationship between Deka-Bank and provincial banks was raised again and again.
Recently, however, Günther Merl, the chairman of the board of Helaba, spoke out against the merger plans with his bank.
Regardless of this, there is a realization that there is a need for the various banks in the commercial sector to approach each other.
Now, after the state assembly elections in Bavaria, the first thing expected is the relationship between BayernLB and Landesbank Baden-Württemberg.
This is not necessarily good news for Helaba.
If the pressure for further mergers increases, it may gradually run out of potential partners.
In southern Germany, it could only be a junior business partner, even though it has weathered the financial crisis significantly better than the Munich and Stuttgart banks.
The merger with WestLB was ruled out at the beginning of the year by Giroverband Hessen-Thüringen, which has an 85% stake in Helaba.
For lack of a better name, it remains NordLB.
However, such geostrategic considerations are only one side of the coin.
On the other side, the question arises as to how the different business models of each bank fit together.
Merl stated in June that the German Association of Savings and Credit Unions has not yet given an answer to the crucial question of what business model should be used to ensure the future of provincial banks.
Finally, the dismemberment of WestLB is also conceivable, which, however, they do not want there as a matter of course.
Thus, the letter from the board of directors there states that they are definitely striving for a &quot;complete solution&quot;.
How this can be reconciled with the merger of the individual units with Deka-Bank is still the music of the future.
