Sleepless nights for Hypo Real Estate lenders
The German banking system is relatively stable, Federal Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück emphasized just last week.
It is fortunate that the politician used the word &quot;relatively&quot; and even included in his speech that the German banking sector is not spared by crisis-like developments.
Because this happened this weekend.
Daxon-listed Munich-based real estate financing company Hypo Real Estate (HRE) received a billion dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself against market turbulence.
A person with knowledge of the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan subsidies amount to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part used.
The money comes partly from private and partly from public banks.
The background lies in the losses of the Depfa subsidiary.
According to a newspaper report, Depfa, which carries out state financing, lent money for long-term projects and refinanced itself for an extremely short term - which is now not possible due to the distrust prevailing in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank&#39;s cash reserve decreased by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, and the share of equity decreased moderately, from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions fell to zero compared to the same period of the previous year, and income from credits for receivables and specified securities, as well as from the liquidation of loan business provisions fell by more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
Only thanks to the higher income from the reimbursement of the subsequent settlement costs of the transformation of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the levy decree and the business brought to the companies belonging to the concern, the revenue deficit of around 16% was relatively moderate.
After privatization in 1990, the former state financier first speculated with corporate real estate loans, which were later segregated in Aeral Bank.
Since there was little to be gained with classic state financing, Depfa threw itself more strongly into infrastructure projects and joint projects between private investors and the state (private-public-partnership, PPP), and expanded its activities internationally.
Hypo Real Estate must now write down the value of its subsidiaries that has a &quot;significant impact&quot; on the group&#39;s income statement, they said quite generally.
It is a fact that no dividend was paid.
By 2007, the dividend had already been reduced to a third.
Since taking over Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has become a major state and infrastructure financier.
Compared to other financial institutions, it is more dependent on interbank market refinancing, as it does not have customer deposits.
With the collapse of US investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has dried up as banks conserve liquidity.
