Rats have feelings too.
A rat or a moth flees in case of danger. Does this mean you feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: Animals have emotions too.
But how can we check if they feel the same when they behave like us?
Famous scientists have been publishing their articles in the Internet journal &quot;Edge&quot; for years.
In one of SPIEGEL ONLINE&#39;s series, &quot;What do you think is real, without being able to prove it?&quot; select from the answers received to the question.
I believe that animals have emotions and other states of consciousness, without me or anyone else being able to prove it so far. It is true that we cannot even prove that other people have consciousness.
In this case, however, we can at least hope that the basic configuration of all human brains is the same.
However, as soon as we look at other species and dissect issues of perception or consciousness in general, we get into difficult terrain because the hardware doesn&#39;t match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: It pretends to be dead, runs away or attacks.
People behave in similar ways, from which some researchers infer comparable subjective experiences.
However, I do not believe in this.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our own subjective experiences to those of animals.
On the one hand, circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its role in short-term memory and executive/control functions).
This broad area is more highly developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other organisms.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, such as the awareness of who we are, or the ability to plan and make decisions, it is reasonable to assume that humans differ even from other primates.
Another dramatic feature lies in the linguistic nature of man: Because a significant part of human experience is related to language, it is often claimed that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals may be excluded.
However, even if consciousness did not depend on language, language would certainly influence it, so animal consciousness, whatever its nature, is likely to be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to establish what consciousness might be like in the case of other animals.
If consciousness cannot be measured as an internal and subjective thing, and because of the special hardware it cannot be analyzed based on our own experiences, then your research presents us with serious problems.
Most of my explanations concern the content of conscious experience, but there is also another aspect of consciousness that is probably more accessible to science.
The conscious processes of animals could be examined regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in experiments on primate short-term memory, especially in the example of visualization.
However, during this assumption, also examined by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, they rely more on the neural connections of consciousness than on causal mechanisms: Both may or may not be the same.
Interestingly, this assumption also emphasizes the importance of the prefrontal cortex in the creation of visualization.
What does this mean for emotions?
I attribute this to the fact that an emotional system, like that of fear, is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call &quot;fear&quot; is therefore the mental state we are in when the activity of the defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) occupies working memory.
Examined in this way, emotions are closely related to those areas of the cerebral cortex that are characteristic of primates and especially humans.
In addition to language, perception is divided into subtle degrees, because with the help of words and grammar, we are able to distinguish and categorize states in order to describe them to others as well as ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, is of the opinion that emotions arise from the simpler activities of the body perception areas of the cerebral cortex and brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who, however, focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could easily play a role in emotions across species.
I cannot refute this purely theoretically, but I consider it unprovable.
Pankseep believes that what appears to be fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt in both cases: How could one verify that rats and humans feel the same thing when they behave similarly?
A cockroach runs away in case of danger, does it also feel fear?
In my opinion, mere similar behavior is not proof of the same experience.
Although the neural comparison helps further: rats and humans have similar brainstems, while cockroaches don&#39;t even have a brain.
But is the brainstem responsible for emotions?
And even if this could be proven in humans: how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have emotions.
However, I don&#39;t know how to prove this.
And since their emotions are suspected to be fundamentally different from ours (since human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I research the emotional behavior of rats rather than their emotional feelings.
In any case, progress in this area is promising at the neural level, if we measure the same thing in rats and humans.
Just as I do not research language and consciousness in the case of rats, neither do I research emotions, since I do not know whether they exist.
To others, this may seem like a short-sighted attitude, but I&#39;d rather move forward than keep hitting a wall.
After all, I am a practical emotionalist.
