Turkey&#39;s expanding diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps only 20 paces from the European border, stands one of the grandest relics of a failed imperial aspiration.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that&#39;s what the guidebooks say.
The building wraps around the end of the platforms, with a tower at the front corner of each, and looks like a German country town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is a bit run down.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large-scale enterprise this westernmost gate was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, the &quot;late future&quot; of conquests, wanted to realize its ambitions to conquer the Middle East with the help of this railway leading from Damascus through Baghdad to today&#39;s Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
Its railway lines were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha station did not fare any better.
In 1917, an ammunition train exploded and destroyed the building&#39;s elaborate roof.
According to Turkish sources, a sabotage action took place.
Since then, it has slowly fallen into disrepair and has been well overrun by history.
At the same time, today, as the railway gate to Anatolia and the entire eastern region, it serves - at least in a symbolic sense - as Turkey&#39;s expanding diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new policy is characterized by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government maintains good relations with Israel and Syria, the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, Iraq, Iran, and, of course, the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to gauge the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP&#39;s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish parliament member Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, approx. after ten and a half hours of jostling, which at the time provided the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, &quot;The Night Mail&quot;, I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is intended to be a symbol of the new, secular state, turning its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This raised some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern, purpose-built stone and steel building - located in a developing suburban area, between half-finished shopping malls and coffee houses. In the latter, middle managers in suits - both men and women - meet to make deals early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have fit in as a centre-right politician in any other European country.
He wore a suit and tie and I&#39;m sure he even had a Blackberry.
&quot;The party&#39;s foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War overturned the order,&quot; he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn&#39;t choose between the two.
It had to open both ways.
&quot;But is it possible that sooner or later he will be forced to choose?&quot; - I asked.
&quot;Turkey never wanted to be at a crossroads.&quot;
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to here repeated almost mechanically: Turkey&#39;s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the countries surrounding the Caucasus and the Black Sea, benefit Europe and the United States just as much as Turkey itself.
It&#39;s as if they want to convey the message that - figuratively speaking - all of Europe, together with Turkey, can reach Asia and the Middle East on those eastward railway lines.
When I was back at Hydarpasha station, after another mostly awake night, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, the two German gentlemen who oversaw the construction of this ornate structure 100 years ago.
How surprised they would be to learn that Europe&#39;s Middle East ambitions are now largely in Turkey&#39;s hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that at the time Turkey was called the &quot;sick man of Europe&quot;.
