A segregated city, black pride and tribulations
Nestled in the theme park of Greater Orlando - a few miles from all that is glittery, loud and huge - lies a quiet little town where the pride and intricacies of the African-American life experience was born.
Eatonville, the first all-black town to integrate in the country and the childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, is not as simple today as she described it in 1935: &quot;the five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 brown skins, 300 good a city of swimming, lots of guavas and two schools, no prison.&quot;
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee have already visited the annual Zora festival. The Eatonville series of celebrations honor Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
Yet, in many ways, the city he described and turned into a tourist attraction - which is also featured in the Florida guidebook published by the Crisis Era Alliance Writers Project - stands apart from its surroundings.
It is as independent, dignified, and self-absorbed as it was in the 1930s, when, Hurston wrote, urban blacks in Florida often refused to share their true thoughts with white people who &quot;know so little about us that they don&#39;t know what they&#39;re missing.&quot; .&quot;
Even in a year when black presidential candidate Barack Obama is encouraging an open exchange of ideas about the issue of race, many here distrust the views of outsiders.
&quot;We are very careful about how our story is told,&quot; reported Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here all her life and is a member of the city&#39;s oldest church.
&quot;It must be said correctly.&quot;
Eatonville has long been characterized by the paradox of victory and struggle.
At the same time, it is a historically significant model of black advocacy, but at the same time, it is a community of almost 2,400 people, where poverty rates are twice the national average.
It is partly a literary hub and partly an example of the sometimes looked down upon, sometimes praised, southern, urban, black culture that flourished in the shade of oak trees as a result of American slavery.
It is therefore not surprising that the residents here are both proud and defensive.
And the image of Eatonville has been important since Zora (everyone calls Hurston that way here).
In books like &quot;Mules and Men&quot; (1935) and &quot;Their Eyes Were Watching God&quot; (1937), written in an honest, strong dialect, he introduced his hometown to the world.
Five paragraphs from the Florida guidebook transformed the town, which lies along Route 17. This road leads from the long-forgotten center of Florida to one of the sites of black history and human drama.
Hurston, who was brave as a drumbeat in both life and literature, introduced her readers to the business of Eatonville&#39;s first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then peeked into the more intimate spheres.
He wrote: &quot;To the right of the road we find the modern public school, brown ground with white border, carefully kept yards and playgrounds, tended by Howard Miller, though he can hardly read or write.&quot;
Mentioning Widow Dash&#39;s new husband, she wrote that Lee Glenn &quot;sells all kinds of liquor and anything you might need at the temporary quarters.&quot;
Thus, in a few hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with autonomy, but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Clearly, Fodor&#39;s guidebook presented it differently.
This description really did not please everyone.
&quot;Zora told it like it was,&quot; reported Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls. Hurston immortalized them by quoting from the slick songs men sang about their beauty.
He added: &quot;Some people didn&#39;t like that.&quot;
Hurston is still remembered here as the vivacious eccentric who often visited home after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston stormed into town, he usually arrived unannounced in a rumbling Chevrolet, smoking a cigarette and wearing long pants in a town where people still pride themselves on their dignified dress.
Most people were charmed by it, Franklin said, but many were circumcised.
&quot;People were always happy to see Zora,&quot; Franklin said.
But on the patio overlooking Sabelia Lake, where Hurston was most likely baptized, he added, rocking in his chair, &quot;He never stayed too long.&quot;
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were never republished.
Eatonville, along with most of the world, seemed to have forgotten about him.
Although she was once a popular writer, a contemporary of Langston Hughes, and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major commemorations or large public readings in Eatonville.
&quot;I don&#39;t think they understand how much she enriched the world, or what she left us at all,&quot; said Valerie Boyd, author of the 2003 Hurston biography, Wrapped in Rainbow.
The turning point came in 1980.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane road through the city instead of the two-lane main street, Kennedy Avenue, which played an important role in the life of the community.
The expanding Orlando has already encroached on the Interstate 4 highway connecting the states on the western border of the city.
The proposal came as Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Among other things, forced integration put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, fights over racial mixing gave the community a taste of hatred.
&quot;At that time a group of white boys came over and threw oranges and other things at the people sitting on the side of the road,&quot; Franklin said.
&quot;There was a lady who died of it.
They threw a watermelon out of a car.&quot;
In a 1955 letter to &quot;The Orlando Sentinel,&quot; Hurston questioned the Supreme Court&#39;s decision to mandate forced integration. This is what he said about the Brown v. Board of Education decision: &quot;it insults rather than respects my race.&quot;
Today, residents say that school desegregation, while positive in some ways, weakened the cohesion of Eatonville residents and undermined the confidence of young people.
&quot;Black kids were used to being hugged - I remember that - you would hug your teacher in the morning and at night,&quot; reported NY Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins, executive director of the nonprofit Save the Eatonville Community.
&quot;It took as long as the students and teachers came from the same place,&quot; he added.
&quot;We didn&#39;t hug our white teacher because he was a white teacher — I mean there were cultural differences between us,&quot; Nathiri said.
However, human rights helped to rise many other Zora Neale Hurstons—black writers, actors, and artists who rose above prejudice, as she did, with such sanguine confidence and lines like, &quot;How can anyone deprive himself of the pleasure of my company!
This is unfathomable to me.&quot;
In 1975, Alice Walker made a pilgrimage to Hurston&#39;s unmarked grave and began to fight to restore her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston, written by Robert E. Hemenway, hit the bookstore shelves and elevated her once again among America&#39;s role models.
The road construction project was about to begin just as Eatonville&#39;s most famous daughter was thrust back into the spotlight.
And this time, Hurston&#39;s old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The community started organizing a Hurston Festival in 1988 to show what the county would destroy with its highway.
Thousands of fans attended the inaugural event two years later, and many have returned to the festivities every January since then.
Several years later, the county abandoned its road construction proposal.
&quot;The five-laning of the main road has revitalized the community and put it into full gear, which is a real sense of civic pride,&quot; Nathiri said.
Boyd put it more simply, &quot;Zora saved Eatonville.&quot;
The victory over the road construction project helped change the city&#39;s image of itself.
People living outside the city appeared in increasing numbers, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who started attending church here in 1993, and locals began to reevaluate the past.
Eatonville was placed on the National Historic Register in 1998.
In 2006, the new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened on the resurfaced and beautified Kennedy Avenue.
Eatonville has remained Florida&#39;s cuckoo&#39;s egg: it is only ten kilometers from the center of Orlando, but sometimes it feels like a suburban side street during summer rain; as small as when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Today, 90% of the population is black.)
Outsiders who come here looking for Eatonville&#39;s history and stories are still treated with caution.
Most interviews require prior permission, and some things, such as Eatonville&#39;s oldest mural, painted by a white man and depicting blacks working in the fields, are not allowed to be photographed.
Many people in Eatonville - including the confident teacher Jones, who is particularly attracted to bright red - fear that their segregated community will be misunderstood.
And yet, as the Hurston Festival grew in scope, so did hometown pride.
Young people in particular increasingly see Eatonville as Hurston saw her own race: wonderful, problems and all, no better and no worse, just as proud, creative, industrious, foolish, and confused as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
Franklin&#39;s nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return after college to take a job at the local government or police department, which he says needs help, echoes a sincere sense of civic engagement.
And the younger ones, like 11-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
&quot;Most people who are just passing through here think this town is nothing compared to the others,&quot; Alondra Kenon said after a service on a recent Sunday.
&quot;But if you stop and take some time to learn about its history, it&#39;s a very beautiful city.&quot;
Here in New York, we all speak the language of finance
On the surface, nothing has changed.
If tourists didn&#39;t mind the newsstands and giant television projectors in Times Square, they wouldn&#39;t realize they were in the middle of a storm.
They would never realize that with the glass-walled, beehive-shaped offices above their heads, the bankers and venture fund managers who hold New York in their power are living through the hardest days since 1929.
Couriers still rattle their metal tea carts down the sidewalks, delivering trays laden with muffins to morning meetings.
Spanish-speaking men still shuffle between blockhouses, carrying fifty or so ironed shirts like human mules, which hang from yoke-like loops over their shoulders.
Office workers still line up for their morning sweet pastries at sidewalk food carts, and it&#39;s still impossible to get a taxi between 4 and 7 on weekdays.
I didn&#39;t feel like there was any kind of crisis until Thursday afternoon, despite all the bad news, I decided to open a new bank account.
Although I had deliberately planned to do it during the afternoon lull at my local JP Morgan Chase bank branch, there were already about 20 people in line ahead of me.
Not at the teller window, where you can withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service desk, where older customers order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to Macy&#39;s, and where new customers open bank accounts.
Many people in front of me - I learned later from Starr, the banker &quot;assigned to me&quot; - had lined up with the same intention as me.
However, unlike me, they have already withdrawn their money from smaller banks where they live, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They took money out of so-called savings banks (which are like housing associations), credit unions, and small-town savings banks that operate in only one state and supposedly treat their customers like family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly gone bankrupt.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in capital, went into receivership, and as New Yorkers headed home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings, was seeking a bailout buyout.
The office and shop workers in front of me, fearing another crash, moved their money to what seemed like a safe haven, the bank that does most of the capital injection buyouts on Wall Street.
Ordinary people in New York have become experts in finance over the past few weeks.
A woman in the local Chinese department store spoke on the phone about the failed Lehman Brothers bank and its powerful-looking CEO Dick Fuld as if complaining about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed caretaker of my apartment block in her fifties, changed the subject, now we weren&#39;t talking about Brad and Angelina or my grocery delivery like we used to.
This is what he said to me after I went to the bank: &quot;I invested all my savings in money market instruments.
I switched, I&#39;m not taking any chances.&quot;
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: Since 1962, as Guildford&#39;s music director, Vernon &quot;Tod&quot; Handley (obituary, Sept. 11) has led the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
Based on his musical plans for the neighborhood, he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
In principle, only people under the age of 21 could be part of the choir, but when Proteus sang its finale in 1979 - many of us were already in our late 20s - we simply refused to part with the choir.
The name &quot;Proteus&quot; (the name of the mythological shape-shifter) was in keeping with the choir&#39;s determination and ability to tackle whatever score was put before it - be it a madrigal or a Messiaen piece; unaccompanied or accompanied by a large orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing and always exciting, and we owe it to the man whose inspiration our enthusiasm for music has remained unchanged over the years.
How often has Tod told us to &quot;let the music speak for itself.&quot;
He always said: &quot;The composer knows what he wants.
Everything is in the sheet music.
So sing it!&quot;
His conducting technique was always completely understandable and precise, but never dictatorial or exaggerated.
Whatever the musical standard, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote about him:
If ever there was a captain who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I got to know him well during the two decades during which he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
I&#39;ve written reviews of more than 100 of his concerts over the past forty-odd years, but he&#39;s never disappointed me with a single one, and often enthused me with them.
Tod Handley had both greatness and modesty, which is very rare.
He hated those commanders who, in his words, simply &quot;galloped around the world with one or two well-known fighters.&quot;
He will be missed by many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
According to your obituary of William Woodruff (September 25), &quot;In 1946 he continued his studies in economic history at Oxford and in 1950 became a fellow at the Houblon-Norman Research Institute...while steadily preparing for his bachelor&#39;s degree, master&#39;s degree and PhD. &quot;
This is from the author&#39;s notes of Woodruff&#39;s &quot;Beyond Nab End&quot;, but it is wrong.
Between 1946 and 1953 he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, and in the meantime, under the guidance of Professor JD Chambers, he completed his PhD dissertation on the British rubber industry, which he published in 1958 under the title &quot;The British Rubber Industry&quot;.
In 1950-51 he was actually in the USA on a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and in the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, New York and Harvard.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for good and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff embellished this period of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria tilts to the right
Heinz-Christian Strache of the right-wing Austrian Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right-wing party Vlaams Belang took part in a demonstration in Antwerp on Thursday, January 17, 2008 to present the &quot;Cities Against the Islamic Conquest&quot; organization.
They marched with signs imitating traffic signs that depicted mosques crossed out with a red line.
Police say far-right extremists are responsible for the desecration of Muslim cemeteries in Austria, the same weekend that far-right parties made significant gains in national parliamentary elections.
More than 90 graves were seriously vandalized at the Traun cemetery near Linz sometime between Friday night and this morning. According to the police, it is an organized action.
The perpetrators spray-painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on some of the graves, but investigators say this was an attempt to hide their extremist motives, which stem from hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is somehow related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were &quot;deeply shocked&quot; by the desecration, which came shortly before the end of the Muslim religious month of Ramadan.
Meanwhile, Austria is having an examination of conscience following yesterday&#39;s parliamentary elections, during which the political balance tipped to the right.
The two far-right parties, which won almost 30% of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, campaigned for a strong anti-immigration law and some of their slogans were branded xenophobic by their critics.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the leader of the Freedom Party, which won more than 18% of the vote, also expressed his displeasure with the campaign against headscarves and burqas and with foods allegedly associated with Islam.
At the party&#39;s final assembly in Vienna, he spoke of &quot;European brotherhood&quot;, with the help of which the strengthening of Islam can be prevented.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets, arguing that they are political symbols of the ongoing Islamization of Austria and Europe.
According to polls and analyzes conducted immediately after the far-right victory, the change was largely due to the young voter base, who are worried about their future in the European Union.
