&quot;I don&#39;t take the photos on stage, because I want to present the artist from a personal perspective&quot; Photographer Günther Bauer
No scenery, no frills, no dancing shoes.
The great masters of flamenco up close, without the excitement of the performance: so that we can also get to know the everyday faces of the dancers.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the ordinary person.
And these two sides cannot be separated, except in the intimate moments, far from the audience, when we can observe a personal movement, grasp the depth of a caught gaze, or marvel at the beauty of the idle but expressive hand of an artist who is not yet preparing to perform on stage.
In his photo series Flamenco-people, the German Günther Bauer combines the theatricality of singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known everyday side of the masters.
Through the photos, he presents the specific iconography of flamenco from different perspectives.
The exhibition, which is part of the Month of Flamenco Photography, &quot;reflects the growing international importance of flamenco every day&quot;, the creator believes, adding that anyone could be the protagonist of Flamenco-people, since the observer realizes that these are images depict artists in a non-typical way.
These people captured on the street are artists who can bring passion, sadness, joy to the stage... and captivate the audience.
At the same time, stage photography is not suitable for capturing their personality.
Their personality and character reside in the deepest part of their being.
I wanted to create an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to use the camera to capture the personalities of the flamenco greats.&quot;
Inspired by the Cante de las Minas festival, Bauer started his long journey in 1997, during which he took portraits of flamenco singers, guitarists and dancers with a plate camera.
Thanks to the camera and the choice of subject, these portraits evoke classical photography.
However, the use of different stylistic devices breaks with traditional pictorial representation and suggests modernity. The following thought faithfully reflects Bauer&#39;s vision of flamenco: &quot;It is a music with traditional roots, but which changes from day to day and is always fascinating.&quot;
It is not the dance, nor the singing or the music per se, but rather the artist&#39;s personality and character that enchants the audience.
The guiding motif of the works that can be viewed in the El Fotómata gallery these days is the search for an encounter with the essential, the artistic charm, which becomes visible through the way of perception, being and display.
The names of well-known figures of flamenco, including Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, are the hallmarks of this photo collection featuring about sixty artists.
The project has also become a flamenco anthology, of which an album including the portraits presented at the exhibition will soon be published.
Bauer&#39;s passion for portraits prompted him to repeat the idea two years ago with the &quot;Portraits of Veteran Athletes&quot; series (&quot;SportARTproject&quot;).
Although the concept of Flamenco-people is slightly different from this, the photographer adds: &quot;I really like photographing people, getting to know them and entering their lives for a longer or shorter moment.
In my opinion, the most difficult genre of photography is portraiture.
Fate brings you together with people you meet, with personalities you sometimes don&#39;t even know, or who only spend a few minutes taking photos.
But despite these circumstances, as a photographer I always try to realize my ideas.
The exhibition entitled Flamenco-people, a selection of contemporary flamenco portraits, can be viewed at El Fotómata Gallery, located at calle de la Mata 20, parallel to Alameda de Hércules, until October 16.
According to Vargas Llosa, the novel he is working on is &quot;complete recklessness&quot;
The location and plot are still unknown to him, but despite all this, Mario Vargas Llosa is busy writing his new novel. The protagonist of the novel is an Irish nationalist, Roger Caseman, who lived in the Congo for twenty years and also visited the Amazon.
The writer, who is also a candidate for the Nobel Prize for Literature, admitted yesterday at the Hay Festival Segovia that his current work is &quot;complete recklessness&quot; and that &quot;all signs point to the fact that the novel should not be written&quot;.
&quot;If I were smarter, I wouldn&#39;t do it, but I&#39;m going to do it and I hope that at some point I&#39;ll be able to put an end to it&quot; - with these words he concluded his presentation at the festival of exchange of ideas, thoughts and opinions, which was hosted by writers, historians and writers for four days in the city of Aqueduct hundreds of journalists and thousands of visitors.
The author of &quot;The City and the Dogs&quot; was one of the most prominent participants in the celebration of literature, and he lived up to the expectations placed on him.
Vargas Llosa won the participant-voted Hay Festival prize for an old edition of Dickens&#39; novel &quot;Our Mutual Friend.&quot; His performance filled the Juan Bravo theater.
After Félix Romeo&#39;s greeting, he was received by a devoted audience. The hour flew by quickly for the audience, during which the Peruvian writer, with an amazing memory and a great deal of humor, told how his writing profession developed from the special adventure of his passion for reading and his desire to live life; how to bridge the lack of inspiration with a disciplined writing method, diligent documentation, lots of corrections and rewrites; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his writing profession, and what memories his stories are based on.
The Latin American novelist admitted that it is impossible to measure or prove whether books change our lives, but added: &quot;I don&#39;t think that literature is just entertainment or a yew-life experience&quot; because it affects people and makes them think. , therefore he asked the writers not to give in to the temptation of lightness and to be responsible for their profession.
