&quot;Blood of May&quot;, an epic work by Garci
Benito Pérez Galdós&#39; National Episodes inspired José Luis Garci, who recalls the famous anti-French uprising of the Spaniards in Blood of May, which, with a budget of nearly 15 million euros, is the largest work in his filmography.
Accordingly, the director attempted to illustrate the flow of people and social analysis he had always admired in the work of the well-known novelist. Garci told all this to a large audience of actors at the film premiere today in the company of Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría.
The two-and-a-half-hour Blood of May will be shown in cinemas on Friday, and Telemadrid will later show it as a mini-series of more than four hours.
José Luis Garci, a great admirer of Galdós&#39;s literature, realized his childhood dream with this shoot. He owes all of this to Esperanza Aguirre, as she commissioned him three years ago from the Province of Madrid to make a commemorative film for the 200th anniversary of the events in Madrid on May 2nd. Garci accepted the invitation on the condition that the story could be based on the National Episodes.
The 15 million budget was entirely financed by the Autonomous Province of Madrid, and it was a special opportunity for Garci: with period scenery and costumes, he was able to present &quot;the confused Spaniards who mistakenly sided with the wrong leader, as the fight for independence pushed the country into great backwardness under Ferdinand VII with his reign,&quot; he said.
However, the director expressed his regret that he could not count on the budget of Alatriste or Goya&#39;s Phantoms, which were more than twice the size of Blood of May. Because of this, he was forced to leave out some scenes from the script, which - as on many other occasions - is written together with Horacio Valcárcel.
So the director of Újrakezdés resorted to his usual working method, recording the scenes with the actors with whom he had already started rehearsals before the shooting. There was no casting because Garci considers it &quot;humiliating&quot; and because, as he said, &quot;part of the craft of directing is going to theaters and cinemas to find out what is going on in the industry in which we work.&quot;
Several actors of Blood of May, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo, were not in front of the camera for the first time.
Garci - who can boast of four Oscar nominations and one Oscar award - believes that none of this year&#39;s nominees representing Spain before the Hollywood Academy, i.e. The Blood of May, The Seven French Pool Tables and the finally selected Blind Sunflowers, are young Spanish cinema. represents his generation, &quot;even though it should be presented,&quot; he said.
Garci does not expect awards with this film.
&quot;In the beginning, you think you&#39;re working for posterity, then you realize that the only thing that matters is prosperity, and in the end you&#39;re happy when one more film is made,&quot; says Garci, with a professional career of almost 30 years behind him.
