Honda sales record for the second time
In November, Honda will start selling the second-generation Jazz.
It is true that the passenger space of its predecessor was already quite large, but the design of the interior of the new model is even more spacious.
All this is combined with sophisticated mechanics that make driving more comfortable and increase fuel economy.
Evolution versus revolution.
This is what the second generation Honda Jazz looks like.
Although the new Jazz looks very similar to its predecessor, a number of internal changes have been made to it.
These include, for example, innovative design, new bodywork, larger dimensions and new mechanics.
But before we move on to the detailed description of the new model, we must say that the new Jazz was released six years after the first generation was launched.
So, first of all, we can state that Honda managed to renew this model in a shorter time than other manufacturers.
Although Jazz is less well-known in Europe, it breaks sales records in other markets.
Such a market is, for example, Japan, where Jazz was the most sought-after car brand in 2002 and again this year in 2008.
In Japan, for example, nearly one million units of the Jazz have been sold since its launch.
The second market was the Old Continent, with nearly half a million copies sold in six years.
Nevertheless, Honda wants to further increase traffic in the region with the new Jazz.
That is, while in 2007 the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 Jazz, for 2009 the estimates aim to sell 100,000 cars, which would result in a 17% increase in the European market.
Since 2002, Honda has sold 8,000 Jazz in the Spanish market, which represents 6.7% of Honda&#39;s total sales in Spain.
In the case of the new generation, the managers of the Spanish subsidiary calculate with 2,000 copies sold within a year.
Moreover, it is the arrival of the new Jazz that will greatly alleviate the decline in Honda&#39;s traffic in Spain.
The company&#39;s representatives predict 22,000 copies sold by the end of this year, which is 4,000 fewer than the 2007 figures, i.e. a 16% decrease.
Despite the terms of the sale, Honda increased its market share in Spain, rising to 1.8% from 1.6% last year.
By 2010, I would also like to increase this ratio to 2%.
Honda hopes to achieve this with the launch of a new model.
This would be the Insight, a five-door and compact hybrid - 4370 mm long - of which the Japanese company would distribute 200,000 units worldwide every year.
According to the Japanese manufacturer, 50% of Insight&#39;s market share would be in the United States, while the remaining share would be divided between the Old Continent and Japan.
The commercial launch of Insight is due in the first months of the year, after the official presentation in Valencia scheduled for January.
Compared to the first generation, the new Jazz has become more spacious in all respects.
Its length reaches 3,900 mm (five centimeters longer), its width is 1,690 mm (two centimeters wider) and the wheelbase has increased by five centimeters, i.e. 2,500 mm.
However, its height remains unchanged at 1520 mm.
In addition to the dimensions, the passenger compartment has also become more spacious.
The larger interior space is guaranteed on the one hand by the new bodywork and on the other hand by the fuel tank located in the middle - this solution is already known from the previous Jazz.
Furthermore, the total cargo space of the so-called double-floor luggage compartment has increased, it is currently 399 liters, i.e. 19 liters more than the capacity of the first generation.
Although this includes the fact that the mentioned dimensions refer to the type with a 1.4 engine, because the trunk of the 1.2 Honda Jazz is 379 liters.
Some external modifications can also be discovered, such as the rear LED lights or the optional panoramic glass roof, as well as easier access to the rear seats.
In addition, the opening angle of the doors belonging to the rear seats has been increased to 80 degrees, compared to the opening angle of 67 degrees in the first Jazz.
The engines of the second generation Jazz are also new.
At the beginning of its sales, this small model can be ordered with two engines, 1.2 and 1.4 liters.
Thanks to the i-VTEC technology, the consumption of both resources is more favorable than the previous model, and it is characterized by lower carbon dioxide emissions and excellent mechanical coordination, while at the same time the engine provides excellent performance in all respects.
The output of the 1.2-liter engine is 90 horsepower at 6,000 rpm, and its maximum torque is 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had 78 horsepower in the previous Jazz - consumes 5.3 liters and emits 125 grams of CO2.
And the other engine, which produced 83 horsepower in the previous generation, now reaches 100 horsepower.
The 100 hp 1.4 Jazz consumes an average of 5.4 liters and emits 128 grams of CO2.
