The collision-avoidant &quot;bee car&quot;
For the development of accident prevention technologies, this time Nissan took inspiration from nature, more precisely from the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company has designed a robot that avoids accidents by imitating the flight of bees.
A device called the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, may be the first step in the development of collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers from Nissan Motor Co.&#39;s Advanced Technical Center, in cooperation with the renowned Tokyo University&#39;s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, built this small robot in Japan.
According to Kazuhhiro Doi, Brand Director of Technology PR and Research Development, the BR23C is a further extension of Nissan&#39;s four-layer safety envelope.
The robot completes the collision avoidance capability of the company&#39;s products.
In flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, very similar to Nissan&#39;s safety envelope.
However, the role of the bee&#39;s compound eyes is much more important than this, with which it can see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees. Consequently, the bee can fly undisturbed in its own personal space.
To copy the function of the compound eye, the engineers designed a so-called laser range finder (Laser Range Finder).
The instrument identifies obstacles up to 2 meters in front of the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an action to avoid a collision.
&quot;As soon as an obstacle is detected, the small robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle in order to avoid a collision.
The main difference between the system and the currently available instruments is that in this case the evasive maneuver takes place completely automatically.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike the bees, the evasive maneuver cannot be directed up or down, nor diagonally, it can only move in two dimensions and only in the direction of the turning of the wheels, that is, not in an infinite direction and way, as is the case with the bees.
That&#39;s why, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used a rotation function in the robot to avoid collisions.
&quot;This structure only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need to store data or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption even with only a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but we are not really talking about gigabytes, but we are not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate crash prevention technology, which Nissan estimates could enter production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system may be an additional possibility of application in order to get the motorist to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
