Alcolock would prevent this, since the system connected to the vehicle determines the alcohol level of the air blown into it. If it is greater than the permissible limit, or if the driver has not blown into the device at all, the system will not allow the car to be started.
The cost of the instrument, which is more than 1,000 euros, would be borne by the violator.
A relevant 2007 study in the USA proved that vehicles equipped with such instruments can reduce the number of violations by up to 65% in the first year after installation.
And in Spain, according to estimates, this rule could save the lives of 115 people every year.
The measure focuses on violations for two reasons: on the one hand, it is easier to prevent them from turning into crimes,
on the other hand, it is easier to introduce, since the implementation of the legal reform takes place in the usual way, while the necessary criminal justice reform would require an amendment to the Basic Law.
The instrument is not yet available in any commercial form on the Spanish market, although it has already been installed in some industrial and public service vehicles in experimental mode.
