Those who talk in their sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don&#39;t mean the ones who wake up and tell me fully awake what happened to them that day, but the ones who talk in their sleep.
The phenomenon may seem scary at first, but it is actually completely harmless.
This benign sleep disorder is called somniloquism.
It is quite common, especially among children and adolescents.
They must have told several of them that he talked at night.
In terms of frequency, it can be completely rhapsodic (for example, it occurs only once in an illness with high fever) or more regular (once a day, week or month), and usually the next day the child does not remember anything.
Its appearance cannot be traced back to a single underlying cause.
It is often combined with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, waking up at night, bedwetting at night (enuresis nocturna) or sleepwalking, but this is also not legal.
As we have already mentioned, it can be a condition accompanied by a high fever, or even a stress or heightened state of excitement.
In any case, it has been little studied until now.
The intensity of speech is also very variable.
It can be quiet, calm, it can consist of incoherent words, mumbling, but in contrast to all of these, it can also occur in the form of shouting, crying or longer speech.
If the phenomenon is very intense, it is recommended to observe the child and contact a specialist. The examination can reveal whether there is an underlying problem causing great anxiety and thus offer a solution.
As already mentioned, it is a benign phenomenon, and therefore there is no cure for it, unless it is accompanied by some other treatable form of sleep disorder (for example, insomnia or stress).
However, there are some things we can do, here are a bunch of preventive measures:
Make sure the child stays calm before going to bed.
Let&#39;s choose soothing games and avoid the child watching fear-inducing or more aggressive TV shows or series.
We teach children who are prone to nervousness or who find it difficult to relax some relaxation methods to help them find inner peace.
This helps the child sleep more peacefully.
If he does start talking in his sleep, try to keep calm.
Remember, this is harmless to the child and they won&#39;t remember anything the next day.
Useful advice
Do not wake the child.
It would be unnecessary, because the child is not conscious, but it would wake him up from sleep.
Even though he talks, he actually continues to sleep and rest.
Remember, if the phenomenon is accompanied by severe anxiety several times, it is recommended to consult a specialist or find out what is causing the child&#39;s high level of anxiety.
If he speaks intelligibly (which is the rarer case), don&#39;t start asking him questions to find out anything from him.
It would be unnecessary anyway, since he is not conscious enough to gather his thoughts during sleep.
On the other hand, you only hear the speech, but you do not see the dream images associated with it, so be careful with the interpretation of what you hear and the possible conclusions.
Never tell the child that they can ask him about his secrets at night.
Not even as a joke.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
So the most important thing is not to worry, as it is only a harmless episode of a few minutes.
