The hostages were forbidden to speak to the press and were immediately transferred to a hospital in Maadi, a residential area on the outskirts of Cairo, where they were examined.
The hostages are &quot;healthy&quot; and the kidnappers &quot;were not paid a ransom,&quot; Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said at the airport.
The hostages were captured on September 19 at the foot of Mount Ouanat in the border region of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they were taking part in an off-road safari. The group was then dragged from one hiding place to another by the 35 unknown hostage takers.
There were 11 tourists in the group (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman), as well as eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency that organized the safari.
According to an Egyptian security chief, a 30-member special commando arrived on the scene in two helicopters, where they raided the hostage-takers just before dawn.
&quot;A firefight broke out between the troops. Half of the kidnappers were killed, the rest fled,&quot; said the leader, who asked to remain anonymous.
He also said that a special squad of 150 people was sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where they were supplemented by German and Italian commandos.
Italian diplomatic chief Franco Frattini, currently in Belgrade, emphasized the role of secret agents and Italian special action groups.
&quot;We have to admit that we could not have achieved this result without the professional and effective intervention of our secret service people and action teams,&quot; he said, without giving further details.
He also denied that ransom was paid for the hostages.
The previous day, the Sudanese army announced that they had intercepted an SUV in which the kidnappers were traveling while on patrol. Six of them were killed (including the Chadian leader) and two were arrested.
According to the army, the hostage-takers were connected to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the organization immediately denied.
Lettres - The &quot;silent majority&quot; of culture
The debate about the funding of culture is currently at the center of the news and the current election campaign.
We can only be happy about that.
But a part of our cultural life is still being forgotten.
Who will speak up to highlight the ridiculous sums of money that small museums, archives, archeological digs and national historic sites on the brink of starvation are earning?
What politician dares to remind the federal government that it does not care about its monuments and heritage buildings?
Or that there are no laws in Quebec or Canada that really ensure the effective protection of our cultural heritage?
