When will someone stand up for the protection of historical and cultural heritage?
Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday. President Dr. Francine Décary had good reason to celebrate because Héma-Québec has now become one of the safest and most efficient blood donation societies in the world.
And most importantly, he succeeded in regaining people&#39;s trust, which was severely shaken by the tainted blood scandals of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserve managed by the Canadian Red Cross blood supply service was infected with the acquired immunodeficiency syndrome (HIV) and hepatitis C viruses in the 1980s.
Following the drama and general uproar, the Government of Canada launched an official investigation in February 1994, led by Judge Horace Krever. The purpose of this was to shed light on the circumstances that led to the tragedy and to make recommendations to avoid similar cases in the future.
While Judge Krever delayed submitting his report, some provinces formed their own commissions to design a new blood system for Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee performed this task.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two blood services were created in Canada: Héma-Québec, which serves Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society, which is responsible for all other provinces and the two territories.
&quot;When Héma-Québec began operations in 1998, only 38% of people had confidence in Québec&#39;s blood supply system,&quot; recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was desperate.
&quot;In the following years, however, as a result of improving the safety of blood products and our work in the field, we managed to regain people&#39;s trust.&quot; Décary proudly states that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population already considered Héma-Québec reliable.
However, Dr. Décary does not forget that &quot;trust is an extremely fragile thing&quot;.
Since its foundation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the principle of prudence.
During this period, a number of cases were discovered in Europe in which mad cow disease, i.e. the new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, also infected people - says the doctor, who has managed the company since its foundation in 1998.
&quot;We had no idea if this disease was spread through blood.
Therefore, we relied on one of the most important recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports. According to this, if we are uncertain about this and there is a risk of developing a serious disease, then we must apply exclusionary measures. In this case, it was Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which causes changes in the brain and thus inevitably leads to death.
Therefore, in April 1999 we did not accept blood from people who had spent more than one month in the UK since 1980.
And a few years ago, it was established beyond any doubt that the disease is also spread through blood.
This case convinced us that it made sense to apply the precautionary principle.&quot;
In 1999, a technique appeared on the market that enables a much more sensitive diagnosis of the HIV virus. This is the nucleic acid test (NAT), which can directly detect the virus itself in the blood of blood donors, rather than the antibodies formed against the virus, on which the previously used tests were based.
With the help of the NAT test, we were able to shorten the window period, which lasts from the time of infection until we can detect the virus in the blood with the help of our technical devices - explains the specialist.
They were able to reduce this period to less than a week.
In this way, the risk of blood donors unknowingly contaminating the blood pool was significantly reduced, as well as that this could not be detected.
These developments greatly reduced the risk of AIDS being transmitted through blood transfusions.
Today, the risk of someone receiving HIV-infected blood is 12 million to one.
&quot;In other words, this means that we would have to distribute 12 million blood products until someone is infected with the HIV virus.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it would take more than 24 years for such a case to occur and for someone to become infected with the HIV virus through a blood product.
I think that today anyone can safely accept or prescribe a blood transfusion in order to restore health - claims the number one leader of Héma-Québec.
&quot;The challenge of the coming decade will be to maintain the reliability of our products.
We never know what new pathogens will enter the system.
After all, it was only last year that the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, enters the blood through an insect bite.
That&#39;s why we have to be constantly alert,&quot; Dr. Décary continued, then emphasized that Héma-Québec must ensure sufficient permanent reserves in addition to emergency reserves.
&quot;As the population ages, so do the demands.
As cancer treatments have become more aggressive, patients often need replacements of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also affects the pool of blood donors, since the number of people in the network who are eligible to donate blood is only 3% of the Quebec population.
However, any healthy person at least 18 years of age who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
Blood is not accepted from an average of 14% of applicants because, for example, they are infected with AIDS or malaria. Those who have visited a country where malaria is ravaging are not eligible to donate blood for one year.
&quot;With this 3 percent, we have enough reserves to meet the needs of hospitals.
It is very rare that we run out of stock.
On the other hand, we need to increase the number of blood donors to the extent that the existing ones get older, because after a while they can no longer donate blood.
But it is very difficult to convince people to donate blood, and it is even more difficult to keep them and make them become regular blood donors.
In today&#39;s fast-paced world, people hardly have a single hour to go and donate blood,&quot; laments Francine Décary.
Operating on an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec provides not only blood products but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeball tissue and skin tissue, which is used almost exclusively for severely burned people.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen, then deposited at Héma-Québec, which also manages Québec&#39;s only public stem cell bank.
Blood that is rich in stem cells can be obtained from the umbilical cord, which was previously only treated as medical waste, and thus enables the treatment of serious diseases (e.g. leukemia).
&quot;A few weeks ago, we celebrated the fact that the thousandth sample of umbilical cord blood entered our bank, and we plan to collect more than a thousand new samples every year.
At the beginning of next year, we will probably start offering these for organ transplants,&quot; clarified Dr. Décary, who says that the umbilical cord blood collection program is very popular these days.
&quot;Many mothers are sad that they don&#39;t have the opportunity to do this&quot; - this is indeed the case, since Héma-Québec is unable to make this complex and expensive program available in every hospital in Québec.
