Charest&#39;s Northern Aspirations
The Prime Minister does not rule out that the election will start this year
As soon as the meeting of the Liberal Party ended, Jean Charest already traveled to Jean-Talon, Quebec yesterday, where the new Minister of Health, Yves Bolduc (left), is aiming for victory in today&#39;s by-election.
&quot;To push back our last great northern border&quot;: this is the ambitious long-term goal formulated by Jean Charest at yesterday&#39;s meeting of the Quebec Liberal Party in Lévis. The speech was also enriched with visual elements, but at the same time the president tried to concentrate on the essence.
During his performance, sequences similar to &quot;Moulin à images&quot; were projected behind him.
On the three giant projectors, impressive images followed each other: hydroelectric dams, mining, Québec on &quot;Google Maps&quot;, maps...
Such spectacular devices are used during election periods.
At the press conference, however, the prime minister refused to guarantee that the election would not start this fall, although he added that his schedule was very tight.
The &quot;northern plan&quot; is the fourth pillar of the prime minister&#39;s &quot;vision&quot; for the future of Quebec, which is embodied in a &quot;new economic area&quot;. This includes a labor agreement with France, an agreement between Canada and Europe, and several planned agreements with Ontario.
Recently, the opening to the North (ie the northern area starting at the 49th latitude) has often been mentioned in the prime minister&#39;s speeches, but he has never given a lecture on this topic.
However, the head of state limited himself to explaining why he considers the North to be &quot;a treasure trove full of enormous possibilities&quot;. However, he did not talk about the time factor, investment amounts, or a specific order of importance regarding future projects.
He highlighted only a few development opportunities: primarily hydropower plants, forestry and especially mining, which is further stimulated by the growth of countries that are catching up and the reconstruction of state infrastructures.
Charest listed &quot;nickel, zinc, copper, platinum, gold, silver, iron, titanium and even diamonds&quot; in the north.
This territory, which is &quot;twice the size of France,&quot; is &quot;our territory, the territory of Québec.
It is not only with us, but in us,&quot; repeated the head of state, emphasizing that he intends to create a national founding myth.
He emphasized that the development of Quebec was largely determined by the connection with the North: the gold rush in Abitibi, planning work in Quebec, James Bay...
&quot;This is ours, our future!&quot; - he added, after taking a dramatic pause to examine the giant map behind him.
The North, which covers 70% of Quebec&#39;s territory, also includes a part of Labrador, which Quebec has always claimed for itself, the Prime Minister announced at the press conference.
&quot;This is our historic position, which has been confirmed by all governments.
There is a border line, regarding which there has been no agreement for a long time, and if the opportunity arises, I will reaffirm the same position on behalf of the government,&quot; he stated.
On the other hand, &quot;even in the light of climate change, we have to rethink our point of view regarding the North,&quot; said the prime minister, speaking of the northwestern passage that opens every year as a result of the melting of the polar ice.
In the Prime Minister&#39;s opinion, in this new geopolitical environment, occupying the territory is an important task.
And what about the natives of the area, the Indians and the Eskimos?
The prime minister stated that the government of Quebec pays special attention to them, and that they will benefit a lot from the plan, especially young people.
The two ministers belonging to different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (the latter was the Parti Québécois delegate in Ungava), have already started consultations with around thirty local communities.
The inter-ministerial committee led by Benoît Pelletier, in which Julie Boulet (Minister responsible for transport and natural resources) also plays an important role, also started its operation.
The Prime Minister does not rule out the possibility of a large-scale meeting, &quot;not necessarily a summit&quot;, where &quot;a common vision is created&quot;.
Otherwise, the development of the North would take place in accordance with the principles of sustainable development.
The Northern Plan will be coordinated, systematized and environmentally friendly at the same time,&quot; the prime minister promised.
Jean Charest described this &quot;vision&quot; as being in line with the visions of previous Liberal prime ministers.
&quot;Just like the liberals before us, we think differently: our goal is to create new opportunities for growth and development out of challenges.&quot;
Incidentally, this was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began on Friday with a large cocktail party celebrating the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage&#39;s election as party president.
One of the adopted resolutions proposes that the Beauharnois power station be renamed the Adélard-Godbout dam.
&quot;Politicians of our party, including Godbout, who founded Hydro-Québec, Lesage, who implemented the quiet revolution and the national spread of hydroelectric power plants, or Bourassa, known as the father of James Bay, all knew how to forge the future,&quot; declared Jean Charest.
At the press conference, he cited another - admittedly conservative - work, namely the &quot;Roads to the North&quot; program of John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister between 1957 and 1963.
Regarding the plan for the dam of the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric power plant, President Charest emphasized that the commissioning is planned for 2012.
&quot;Let&#39;s keep this between us, but I plan to be there,&quot; he told his followers, and his statement was met with loud applause.
Indeed, the prime minister, who said in April that there would be no elections in 2008 and probably in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of a vote to be held this autumn, which the law also allows him to do.
However, he emphasized that his calendar is already full, as he has undertaken tasks at the meeting of the federal council in China and the Quebec-New York summit.
The party meeting at the end of the week proved to be an excellent platform for the Liberal president to expound on the nationalist resolutions, which were approved almost without a second thought. Here it is mainly about &quot;constitutional aspirations&quot;: the Liberal Party especially demands the recognition of &quot;Québec&#39;s special character&quot; in the Constitution.
They also want Quebec to be able to appoint members of the Canadian Radio and Telecommunications Council, and for those members to have veto power over decisions made in Quebec.
The opposition, on the other hand, received the main points of the Northern Plan with skepticism.
The leader of the Parti Québécois, Paulina Marois, re-introduced the Northern Quebec development policy introduced by the Landry government in 2001.
According to Marois, the Liberal government that came to power in 2003 refused to apply this policy.
If they hadn&#39;t done it, &quot;we would be much ahead today&quot;, said Mrs. Marois, in agreement with Françoise Mercure, whom she launched as a candidate in today&#39;s Jean-Talon vote.
The ADQ opposition party supports the government&#39;s acceptance of the Northern Plan.
&quot;However, we would like this to be more than just a show,&quot; said party leader Sébastien Proulx, who replaced Mario Dumont, who returned from his vacation today.
Letters - A disgraced country
Vic Toews, a Harper cabinet minister (minister of &quot;justice&quot; by the way) had the nerve last summer to call Louise Arbour a &quot;disgrace&quot; to Canada.
To slander a woman like this, who fought for the truth incessantly and deserves all our admiration, says a lot about the people surrounding the Prime Minister and about Stephen Harper himself.
This is our government, which is the only one of the affected Western countries that did not transport its own citizens home from the Guantanamo concentration camp.
This is the government that completely ignores the fact that Omar Khadr was a teenager at the time of the crimes he was accused of committing.
This is the only government that, despite Canada being a signatory to the Geneva Convention, has reneged on its word and is allowing a child soldier to languish in inhumane conditions.
The only government that makes a puppet theater out of justice while investigating the guilt of a defendant.
Let&#39;s just remember that UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association are demanding Omar Khadr&#39;s repatriation so that he can receive a fair trial in Canada.
And our government turns a blind eye to torture: it does not care that a young adult has already been completely destroyed mentally, and that many years of torture have probably sealed his fate for life.
Although we are not yet aware of this, our rights, freedom and democracy are being insidiously destroyed. &quot;Democracy&quot;: Harper keeps repeating this word, which comes out of his mouth as nothing more than empty words.
So the time has come when morality no longer exists: they can arbitrarily beat, torture and imprison any Canadian citizen at the whim of the head of a government that has so far been in the minority (and what can come after October 14th...?).
Many voters believe that salvation can be found in a party that glorifies Virtue, Law and Order. They do not see that this government is trampling on the values to which our country owes its good reputation and dignity.
Dear Mr. Toews, the shame is more like this - look no further.
Review - Barrick Gold&#39;s Orwellian Oratory
In the September 17 issue of Le Devoir, a letter from Patrick J. Garver, deputy president and general manager of the Barrick Gold mine in Canada, appeared.
Following his Orwellian exposition, Garver states that the world&#39;s largest gold mining company filed a $6 million libel suit against three authors and a small-money publishing company in order to initiate what he calls a &quot;public debate.&quot;
Although the judges are independent and impartial, their decision - especially in defamation cases - is not based on the truth, but on the basis of the law.
Not surprisingly, Garver was deeply silent about this fundamental difference.
Would the best way for Barrick Gold to engage in public debate really be to destroy anyone whose viewpoints conflict with theirs?
Regardless of the outcome of the lawsuit, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada will have to spend significant sums to defend and fight an unequal battle, where on the other side is an army of lawyers supported by the almost inexhaustible resources of the mining industry.
In such an unequal struggle, they often use the tactic of destroying the defendant and reaching an amicable agreement, which not only silences those who disagree, but also intimidates those who would try to address the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have expressed its views in public.
While this is done differently in many of the other countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, disputants generally speak their minds rather than hitting each other with sticks.
Therefore, it would have been enough for the mine to open its books and files and prepare for a real debate in the press, media, and publications, paying for independent research groups that could shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold doesn&#39;t seem to trust public opinion, sweeping aside petitions and letters in defense of Noir Canada&#39;s authors in one fell swoop.
Could Mr. Garver explain how he can initiate a &quot;public&quot; debate while at the same time disregarding the opinions of that public?
In the Deputy President&#39;s mind, this word probably only means the handsomely paid lawyers, and not the entire population of Canada: the meaning of the term thus narrows considerably.
In a democratic state, even those who denigrate others are entitled to freedom of speech.
Barrick Gold, on the other hand, does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the authors and publishers of Noir Canada are mainly supported by the public because it condemns the harsh methods of the mine.
The public is ready to listen to Barrick and form a judgment, but it would do so based on civilized reasoning, not through a lawsuit aimed more at silencing many. (Regarding the term &quot;public debate&quot;, by the way, Barrick Gold recently wrote to the authors of Noir Canada to refrain from using this term.)
Beyond Garver&#39;s surreal revelations, Barrick Gold&#39;s proceedings are an open attack on the freedom of university research and the pursuit of truth, which are the building blocks of any democratic society.
The procedure as a whole denies the right to cite authentic sources, something to debate about the facts and their interpretation, which form the basis of intellectual activities.
If a country like Canada can only study and discuss topics that don&#39;t please the wealthy corporations of today&#39;s world under the burden of litigation, who will have the courage to do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted an open and transparent discussion, it could do so according to the scientific standards that the authors of Noir Canada employ.
You have the right to reply.
In our university circle, we have been able to handle disputes, differences of opinion and conflicts for a long time.
Barrick Gold&#39;s ill-considered course of action clearly shows that, contrary to its claim, it has no desire to engage in an open debate.
This is a loss for both the world of academia and the Canadian institution of public debate. It is time for governments to finally introduce measures to limit legal proceedings for such abuse.
Wall Street bailout - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and the Republican and Democratic leaders of Congress finally reached an agreement yesterday on the economic rescue operation, the largest such plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The $700 billion plan, which aims to curb the financial crisis that has raged on Wall Street for months, still needs to be approved by both houses of Congress.
The essential points of the plan: more effective control of the implementation by the representatives; new mechanisms ensuring repayment of allocated public funds; new provisions to keep the number of houses seized for non-payment at the same level; right of access to the salaries of the managers of the aided companies.
US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the US House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative Judd Gregg announced the good news yesterday, a few minutes before midnight, after the two-day marathon hearing ended.
&quot;We have made great progress toward a solution that will work effectively in the markets,&quot; Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
&quot;We did everything with the aim of saving the real economy and American citizens from the current crisis affecting Wall Street,&quot; the Democratic representative explained.
&quot;The bottom line is that if we don&#39;t do this, there will be tremendous shock, chaos and confusion in the daily lives of Americans,&quot; said Rep. Judd Gregg, Republican.
Negotiations were sped up in the last few hours amid fears that another setback would hurt investor sentiment.
They gave themselves a deadline for the agreement until the opening of the stock market this morning.
The two presidential candidates who joined the negotiations late showed themselves willing to reach an agreement, however, they expressed that they were not happy that the situation had escalated to the limit.
Senator Barack Obama, a Democrat, took credit for expanding the deal to include provisions such as home ownership preservation or the pay of executives at state-backed companies.
&quot;When we&#39;re asking taxpayers to take some extraordinary measures because of other people&#39;s irresponsibility, that&#39;s not a very welcome thing.
However, these steps are necessary,&quot; he said in an American television program.
And when his opponent, John McCain, was asked by another channel whether he would vote for the proposed plan, he replied: &quot;I would like to know the details, but I hope so.&quot;
&quot;From what I have broadly read, it is already clear that it is something that we all have to digest and through which we can move on.
The option of doing nothing is simply unacceptable,&quot; he said.
According to the 700 billion dollar plan, taxpayers&#39; money would be used to buy the dubious claims of American financial institutions and their unsaleable assets exposed to some risk.
The plan was preceded by a 14-month crisis, which was triggered by the bursting of the real estate bubble. This first led to the collapse of risky real estate loans (subprime mortgages), then spread to other debt (commercial) securities, and finally caused the freezing of liquid resources and the turmoil of banks and financial institutions.
The first draft of the agreement was defeated by a group of Republican representatives last week.
We seem to have managed to get out of this impasse since the Democrats agreed that certain &quot;toxic&quot; assets of troubled companies should be secured by the government rather than bought.
To satisfy all members of Congress, the plan also included a provision that, if the government had to bear losses under the program for five years, it could levy new taxes to recoup its funds.
As part of the new plan, a $250 billion installment would be paid first; this can be followed by another 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of the remaining $350 billion would have to be approved by Congress in another vote.
In exchange for the assistance, Washington acquires shares in the supported companies, through which it receives dividends from the profits, which it can sell after the crisis subsides.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the foreclosure of properties used to back the mortgages involved in the plan. In addition, it can set the maximum value of salary and severance pay that can be paid to the managers of companies affected by the crisis.
The drafters of the plan would like the plan to be voted on by the House of Representatives today, and by the Senate on Wednesday.
However, despite their efforts, the plan is still not certain to be approved.
Yesterday, statements against the plan were repeatedly made by both Republicans and Democrats.
&quot;It is abundantly clear that Washington is not hearing your voice,&quot; Republican Scott Garrett, who is a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
&quot;Yes, we have serious financial problems.
Yes, there are solutions.
But there is none that would benefit the taxpayers.&quot;
Brad Sherman, a Democrat who leads a small congressional group called the &quot;skeptic faction,&quot; presents things differently, but reaches the same conclusion.
&quot;Four hundred eminent economists, including three Nobel Prize-winning scientists, have written to us to ask Congress to take its time and carefully consider which path it is taking,&quot; Sherman said yesterday.
In Europe, at the same moment, they understood again that this was a global crisis.
After a crisis meeting, the three Benelux states announced that they would nationalize part of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US dollars).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg came after France&#39;s BNP Paribas said it would not buy its bankrupt rival after losing 2 million euros ($2.9 billion) in the US subprime crisis.
With 85,000 employees, Fortis is one of the twenty largest European banks and one of the ten largest insurance companies.
&quot;This is not wasted money,&quot; said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos yesterday.
&quot;In return, we get voting rights and influence in the bank.
This is exactly the kind of thing that depositors and households are appreciating now that the situation promises to be uncertain.&quot;
Meanwhile, on the other side of the English Channel, the British government seems to be preparing to nationalize another bank that was swept away by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government would take over all of Bradford and Bringley&#39;s ongoing loans, of which real estate loans amount to 41 billion pounds (75.5 billion US dollars).
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that they will acquire the subsidiaries and customer base of the British bank.
After Northern Rock, Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank that the British government wants to nationalize since the beginning of the crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Farewell to the acting idol
Her beautiful azure eyes were considered by some to be her greatest trump card, and to others her greatest weakness.
Has the American actor with the charming smile ever gotten rid of his narcissistic mirror?
Yes and no.
Due to his shyness, sensitivity and innate talent, he was also far from the flamboyant style that is the essence of the real great monsters of the art world.
But what a great course he ran!
Paul Newman died of lung cancer at the age of 83 on Friday at his estate in Connecticut. He was one of the last icons of the heyday of American cinema.
He was less of a monumental individual than Brando, whom he resembled and who was for a long time his rival on the screen. In his roles, he was more restrained and undoubtedly more vulnerable, but he also advocated freedom and the destruction of dramatic conventions.
The mixing of bloods often results in extraordinary children.
Newman was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
European roots contributed to the birth of one of the symbolic figures of the American dream.
He didn&#39;t think too much of himself, which only added to his merits.
After all, a country fond of the ideal image of the &quot;self-made man&quot; and the ideal of the warrior broken in the Pacific War was embodied in him. In the early 1950s, he studied at Yale University&#39;s drama department and then at the Actor&#39;s Studio in New York, before bursting into the world of theater, television, and soon after, cinema.
