What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Tsai?
Soon, on October 8, the trial of the criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his associates will begin.
The politician and his associates are accused of fraud and other crimes, including forgery of documents, which caused particularly significant damage and were committed continuously and commercially in a criminal organization.
According to the prosecutor&#39;s office, the awarded tender funds were used for their own purposes, and the fulfillment of tasks was often verified with false invoices.
The state and municipal funds - a total of about HUF 65 million - went partly into the coffers of the Young Left and partly into the pockets of certain individuals.
The method also described by the investigative authority was that the winning tender funds were taken on the basis of expense accounts that had no actual performance behind them, and the associations never fulfilled their obligations.
According to the indictment, most of the invoices were fake.
The bill blocks for these were acquired at the Józsefváros market, and the circular stamps were produced in Kiskunhalas.
And the name of which companies the invoices should be produced was decided, among other things, on the Balaton-Upland tour on which János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
According to the latter&#39;s testimony, he had to check out boarding houses and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption there, based on which the invoices to be submitted to the tenders of, among others, the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, and the Metropolitan Municipality were prepared.
Most of these were recorded by István Lados with his partner, András Őri, who, according to our information, mostly wrote the reports necessary to obtain the subsidies.
One of the highlights of Lados&#39; &quot;study tour&quot; was a beer house.
According to two invoices issued by the Zuschlags, dated 2003, the restaurant provided meals for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Point Association.
However, according to the company manager, this many people would not have fit into the restaurant at the same time.
In the same way, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 to the Foundation for a Better Future - later named Együtt a Third Éezredért - was full of errors in form and content.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj only had three rooms, no more than ten people could sleep in it one night, yet the bill was for one hundred and thirty guests.
But the imaginative form-fillers also went too far when they flagged Pigal Kft., also engaged in hospitality, whose accounting - according to the information provided to the prosecutor&#39;s office - did not even include documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
The head of the company, Győző Farkas, told hvg.hu that when he was called to the prosecutor&#39;s office and was shown the invoices, he immediately knew that they were fake documents.
&quot;The name of our business and our tax number were in the wrong place on the stamp.&quot;
He added: in addition to formal reasons, the fact that according to the bill they accommodated a hundred people was also inappropriate, because they have a total of eleven rooms, which do not have that many beds.
In addition, the bill was for catering, while their restaurant has been out of business for a long time.
The zealous invoice makers did not even investigate the fact that the Budapest travel agency they were looking for only organizes foreign trips, so they fraudulently marked Hungarian travel as a service on the cash payment invoice, which also did not match the company&#39;s invoicing practice.
In addition, as it turned out during the investigation, VAT was included on the document, even though the travel activity to countries outside the European Union was VAT-free.
Among other things, the amount of VAT was wrong on the four documents issued by Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to Jobb Jövőért, because the company&#39;s services are charged not at the specified 25 but at 15 percent VAT, in addition, the hotel&#39;s employees only issued a machine invoice, whereas the manufactured invoice it was manual.
In addition, the &quot;exhibitors&quot; also messed up the account by indicating that in the case of one company road freight transport was a performed activity - it was revealed through the prosecution procedure - that the company, which was originally based on investment advice, did not carry out.
In addition, due to formal discrepancies - incorrect invoice format, not a real stamp - it was revealed that the Együtt a Third Éezredért Foundation, the XXI. The invoices for Századi Cultural Association and Biztos Pont are fake.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or Kunfehértó Sport Camp, whose representatives denied that they had issued the invoices.
For example, the forgers did not pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft. in Nyíregyháza was under liquidation at the time (2001) when the group of the Young City Association had a meal there, which is why the company&#39;s liquidation commissioner - as far as we know - denied that he had issued it the paper.
It was deliberately put out
Another group of invoice issuers consists of those who were aware that they had to issue a fictitious invoice.
At the request of the Young Left - Young Socialists, the Esély Budapestért Foundation issued an invoice for the Együtt a Harmadik Émezredért Foundation, for about four million forints.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was persuaded by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi, to issue the fictitious invoice.
Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation, also cooperated with the Zuschlags, which in 2003 supplied the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület and the Vöröfenyő Egyesület with invoices for a value of roughly HUF five million, which were not backed by real economic activity.
No cash movement either, because the completed invoices were reversed afterwards, but the organizations forgot to include this in their documents.
The next group of invoice-issuing companies includes those that can be linked to the defendants.
Thus, Iván Kubatov was the delivery representative of the Ukrainian managing director of Delta Trió Kft., which deals in fuel and motor vehicles and is based in Budapest, although it is not located there.
The company issued several invoices in October, November and December 2005 for the sale of computer equipment, worth approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation data, these accounts were purchased by Kiskunhalas Cash Investment Kft., which has been in liquidation since September 14, 2005.
The managing director of this company was a Romanian man, to whom Iván Kubatov would also have forwarded documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
We know that Kubatov admitted during the investigation that the company he issued an invoice in his name to Atlas, Hoppa and the Together for the Third Year Foundation, and he took their consideration.
At the express request of Iván Kubatov, Romanian masons founded Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
However, none of the companies actually operated, which, according to the accused, was because they did not get jobs.
The companies still benefited, because at the request of his co-accused, lawyer Zsolt Szente, who also prepared the company foundation papers, he issued invoices on behalf of the companies to the associations linked to Zuschlag: Atlas and Y-Generation.
On behalf of Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, Kubatov gave a total of 15 invoices to the organizations, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor&#39;s office believed that 10 percent of the amounts indicated on the invoices and the VAT went to Kubatov.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to issue fictitious invoices, which were produced for the Bizto Pont tender.
In January 2006, Generation Y and the Alliance for Modern Hungary submitted an application to the socialist party&#39;s public benefit organization, the Mihály Táncsics Foundation (TMA).
They won HUF 500,000 each, but the amounts were not used for the purposes specified in the tender.
To prevent this from being revealed, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were submitted to the TMA.
Incidentally, these invoices were found during a search of Árpád Kemecsei&#39;s office at the Ministry of Education.
At the trial, some of the defendants, as they did at the prosecution, will probably report on the invoice production process.
It can be most interesting if the prime accused himself, János Zuschlag, decides to lift the veil on everything.
His testimony so far is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to speak comprehensively, he has not yet done so.
It is a question whether he is in this interest, after all, the socialists made a deal with him in exchange for compensating a large part of the damage, fifty million forints, and Zusi will take the trouble.
By the way, he might even have been offended by now, since his requests to ease the conditions of his detention, i.e. to place him under house arrest, have continuously fallen on deaf ears.
While the perpetrators of economic crimes that cause much greater damage and do not compensate for it can walk freely, or at least wait for the end of the proceedings against them in their own homes, he does not have the opportunity to do so.
The psychology of overbidding: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more money and overvalue the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known - and seemingly irrational - behavior were discovered by neurologists and economists at New York University.
According to their study published in the journal Science, people don&#39;t want to lose out in a type of competition like an eBay auction, so they&#39;d rather pay too high a price.
The research tried to map the neural scheme of this &quot;game&quot; with the help of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other group participated in a playful auction, while the active brain areas of the experimental subjects were examined using the functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) method.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction game - in which an important element is the outbidding of the other party - the subcortical complex called the striatum became active when the game was lost.
This brain area plays a role in the &quot;self-rewarding&quot; mechanism of the nervous system, among other functions.
Therefore, according to the researchers, beating the price can be explained by avoiding the intense reaction of the striatum.
To support their theory, the economist members of the research group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In it, three groups bid against one partner under various conditions.
The control group was simply told what the real value of the product was and they placed their bets.
Another group was also promised that if they emerged victorious from the game, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received 15 dollars just before the auction, but the members of the group lost this money as well in the event of a losing auction.
The only difference between the two groups was that one of them emphasized winning and the other emphasized losing.
However, proving the neurologists&#39; hypothesis, the members of the team playing &quot;against loss&quot; were willing to place higher stakes than the control and &quot;winning&quot; groups.
&quot;These results cannot be derived from any previously existing economic theory.
Until now, they have only explained the phenomena experienced at auctions with the joy of winning and risk avoidance.
Only neuroimaging methods have helped resolve the contradiction between these two theories, so that we have now arrived at a third explanation,&quot; said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
About half a billion people in the world suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and chronic liver disease is mentioned among the leading causes of death in Hungary.
The number of people infected with hepatitis in Hungary can be as high as 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, hepatitis and jaundice are typical, but their pathogens and the diseases they cause are different.
Depending on the causative agent, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis A and E through the alimentary canal (e.g. through contaminated food and water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal discharge, saliva).
Travelers should definitely get vaccinated against viruses A and B, there is no vaccine against C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal complaints, and nausea.
After this, the skin and the whites of the eyes develop yellowness, the stool becomes light, the urine becomes dark, and recovery may take two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from the more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that, according to estimates, only every tenth infected person receives drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know they have the disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20-30 years later.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening tests are very important.
Three groups have much more of this disease than average: among people who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users and those with tattoos.
Currently, the number of people infected with the chronic hepatitis C virus in the world can be estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory test, it is worth contacting your family doctor if you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
If detected in time, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the infectiousness ceases and the development of cancer can be prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by patient organizations around the world.
Its purpose is to draw attention to chronic hepatitis caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early detection of the disease.
Benelux governments nationalize a part of Fortis bank
The Benelux countries are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to get into trouble due to the spillover effect of the American credit market crisis, with partial nationalization: the three countries are supporting the financial and insurance institution, which also has interests in Hungary, with a total of 11.2 billion euros.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments negotiated the matter at the highest level at the end of the week, including the president of the European Central Bank and the competition officer of the European Commission.
In the Eurozone, Fortis Bank&#39;s is the first major crisis within the framework of the international financial market crisis that has been raging in waves for more than a year, and the decisions made in the bank&#39;s case can therefore be classified as precedent-setting from a certain point of view.
According to the decision made on Sunday night, all three states will buy almost half (49 percent) of the bank&#39;s existing property there.
The bank will certainly sell some of its interests, including, above all, the - mainly insurance - activities it bought from the Dutch ABN Amró last year.
The shares of Fortis began to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week serious crisis phenomena were already visible at the institute.
However, analysts agree that the bank, with its 85,000 employees, is too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
The company&#39;s shares fell by around 12 percent to a 14-year low on Friday alone.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Looking at the current share prices, the group&#39;s total market capitalization is around 14 billion euros, but according to company managers, this is not realistic.
By the way, the company management blamed overseas market uncertainties related to the acceptance of the US$700 billion package plan for the drop in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the papers rose slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but so far no one has come forward with a meaningful offer.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors do not need to worry, they will not lose their money.
So far, there has been no panic among the bank&#39;s clients, and the branches have not been raided.
In Hungary, Fortis has an independent branch and has also acquired leasing companies.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to the results of a recent research, religious faith acts as a kind of pain reliever, which may have made the death of Catholic martyrs easier.
Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, investigating how faith in God affects people&#39;s perception of pain, the British Telegraph reported.
In the framework of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were given electric shocks while they were all studying a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to block out most of the pain.
Thanks to the technique of scanning the human brain, it was also revealed that the Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
The investigation is the first in a research series in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university are also participating.
The test took place precisely by attaching a sparking device to the subject&#39;s left hand, which delivered the electric shock.
The researchers asked participants to look intensely at two paintings, Sassoferrato&#39;s 17th-century Virgin Mary and Leonardo da Vinci&#39;s 15th-century Lady with an Ermine.
The authors of the study hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would induce a kind of religious state among believers, while the da Vinci image was chosen because it was not too different from the other and was thought to have a calming effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner machine, during which time they received 20 electric shocks in four consecutive parts while looking at either the religious-themed or the general image.
The Catholics reported that when they saw the Virgin Mary, they felt &quot;safe&quot; as someone who was &quot;taken care of&quot; and &quot;calm down, filled with peace&quot;.
They reported 12 percent less pain while looking at the religious-themed picture than when they saw Leonardo&#39;s work in front of them.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself participated in the study, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with any powerful image, including atheists, you just need to find the right photo.
&quot;We should find an image that they feel very positive about, like a mother or a father.&quot; said the psychologist.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
&quot;Exercising faith should and in many cases does change our personality.&quot; Wright added.
After the excellent results, the only question is, if Leonardo or a painter of a similar caliber showed the faithful a picture of a Madonna, what effect would it have on their pain control?
Would the sight of a quality Virgin Mary mean even better results?
You are what you share about yourself
On its tenth birthday, Google can say: it can be found in people&#39;s pockets at least as much as it is in the sky above their heads; you know where they vacationed, what appointments they attend and what they are interested in.
And this is still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the main people of the company.
As for the skeptics who draw parallels with the Orwellian nightmare, they do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google&#39;s main goal is to collect even more personal data about its users, which is necessary for them to be able to stick to the original goal of Google&#39;s founders, which was: &quot;to systematize the world all your information!&quot;.
According to the interviewed Google leader, even after ten years of world-shattering work, the company is still only at the beginning of being able to handle all the information.
When asked what will happen five years from now, Schmidt said he wants Google to be able to answer questions like &quot;what should I do tomorrow?&quot; or &quot;what job would really suit me?&quot; - however, until then, the software cannot answer such seemingly simple questions, because they do not know enough about the users.
Not all internet users are aware that search terms are recorded exactly during internet searches, from which IP address they were searched and to which page the interested party left after the search.
With Personalized Search, which was launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own surfing background history, look back at what they searched for, what they clicked on, and through this it will generate much more personalized results for them in the long term - Recommendations will be based on the same logic, with which it recommends products and services for us, the system is based on our previously stated and recorded preferences.
What if they use my data against me if they see what I do for a living? - ask users who are worried about Google&#39;s data monopoly.
In most cases, the degree of potential power represented by the company can be frightening, not the guilt, the fear of punishment, the desire for freedom, but rather the rebellion against the power that causes the counter-reactions among Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that all searched terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases they can also be transferred to third parties, in such legal cases nothing protects the privacy rights of Internet users.
The loudest example of this in recent times was perhaps the concerted action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google provided the Brazilian government with information about pedophiles that enabled identification from the social media site it maintains called Orkut.
On the other hand, Internet users concerned about privacy rights could breathe a sigh of relief in May, when the company, together with the electronic rights protection organization EFF, successfully proved its case against the FBI in court: according to them, Google cannot be forced by any point of the constitution to comply with the FBI&#39;s secret requests in the future. provide any information.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully seized about fifty thousand web addresses and a thousand search terms, obtained by citing the strengthening of child protection laws passed years earlier, but was still unable to obtain search lists of individual users, or a full two-month list of websites and keywords .)
Google&#39;s assessment is therefore quite contradictory: those who are afraid of giving out their personal data, because they feel that their intimate sphere and privacy are being violated by starting to use Google&#39;s services, are whipping it up with a rebellion that is typical of multi-companies with a conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its wild drive of enthusiastic computer fans, activists, and users appearing in many countries sees them as the next generation of large companies, the &quot;cool corporation&quot;, in contrast to its rival, Microsoft, which is billed as a world conqueror due to Windows, no matter how much both struggle. for the same purpose.
This may happen because, unlike Microsoft, Google does not ask its users for an identification code or charge money for its applications, the open, free, constantly updated source code and program package seems much more accessible, younger, and cooler than the official software giant&#39;s practice.
However, it may also be because geeks clearly see the very problematic relationship between privacy rights and the Internet, which has been brought about by one of the most frequently mentioned keywords of recent years, Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about nothing but collaboration, about intentionally leaving traces behind and making use of the communication channels available to us, and while the extent of these varies from individual to individual, the point is the same: we show ourselves.
An average young person can maintain a profile on several social media sites, from Facebook to Xanga, and connect them to other services, such as Twitter, or last.fm, which lists their music habits, and then connect them all to tracking systems such as FriendFeed or Blip. .fm, they can also run a blog, which automatically displays their latest photo galleries stored on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can read about many exemplary cases from which it is clear: the girlfriend can easily find out who her cheating boyfriend spent the evening with after seeing the morning photo stream of the common circle of friends, or she can fire a company employee just because he writes his honest opinion about the top management in his blog: a sure , the concept of privacy has been completely reevaluated by now.
Anyone who lives online is made up of what they show of themselves, and this is how we can formulate the basic premise behind the behavior of today&#39;s young people.
And anyone who wants to hide something, or at least wants to avoid the Google monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, which uses Google&#39;s search system, but at the same time intentionally leaves no trace).
For example, the number of people who deliberately do not register on social networking sites so that they cannot be found is not small. Google&#39;s online applications, from the text editor to the image manager and news reader, can be replaced with alternative versions that are not connected to huge server parks and that do not make up of us the previously existing best profile.
The public is not so secretly waiting for Google to reveal its tooth protein.
At a current valuation of $156 billion, the company is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising platforms threaten the revenues of advertising agencies, the and services introduced at an ever-accelerating pace cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for many other software developers.
However, critical observers also find disturbing counterpoints to these: for example, the top management completely rejected the employees&#39; protest after doubling the company kindergarten fee, the company management found it too expensive to feed the employees as many times a day as they want, but all this is dwarfed by the fact , that Google bowed to the Chinese government back in 2006, and according to their agreement, the company filters out all results that violate good taste and the interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the internal rules of the company is that they do not announce a new service in advance, only when it can be used, but it is certain that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years can move the world at another point: while some believe that Google its book and magazine scanning and archiving project has reached such a scale that the company will soon have to face the US Supreme Court, others are afraid of the Health system, because in it we can build a complete health profile about ourselves with our previous findings, doctors and problems.
And the fact that Google is building a genetic database can also provide good material for the next generation of science fiction writers, the popular Cory Doctorow short story, Scroogled, describes a future in which a person can only use Google data with Orwellian overtones is alarmingly approachable.
