The flight of the dongo is imitated by the intelligent car
What better way to develop collision avoidance technologies than to mimic obstacle sensors found in the natural world?
For example, bees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point for how to build the next generation of collision avoidance systems.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built the BR23C biomimetic car robot control system, a robotic minicar endowed with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to develop a system that eliminates all collisions.
In flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is actually very similar to our safety envelope, Kazuhhiro Doi, Technology PR and R&amp;D Brand Director, explained at the exhibition.
The role of the bee&#39;s compound eye, which can see in all directions at a viewing angle of more than 300 degrees, is important.
To copy the function of that compound eye, the engineers came up with the idea of a laser rangefinder.
This identifies obstacles within 2 meters in a 180-degree field of view in front of the BR23C, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an action to avoid a collision.
The obstacle is detected in a fraction of a second, and then the car robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes direction by turning its wheels to the extent necessary to avoid a collision.
Unlike any current system, this evasive maneuver is completely instinctive.
&quot;If this were not the case, the car-robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,&quot; explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car-robot project.
It must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the safety envelope, a layer within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process should mirror what a bee does to avoid other bees.
This process should take place in the blink of an eye.
But, unlike bees, the deviation cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction of turning the wheels.
In this way, instead of the endless possibilities available for the bees to avoid other bees, here only the rotating movement and acceleration and deceleration were used as the available options of the car robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they last longer than the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is important, not the ability to process, much less store, data.
This structure only needs to process and respond to a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn&#39;t need to store them and reacts with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of memory all the time.
You don&#39;t need gigabytes or even megabytes of memory.
It&#39;s the first step in the development of instant-avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates could be in production cars within ten years.
Another application possibility is the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the motorist to the specified final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
The expensive child also got a name
The written version of the 700 billion dollar economic rescue package law, which is applicable in several installments and aims to buy bad loans of banks, has been prepared.
In the first round, half of the amount is spent.
According to Reuters, during the new negotiations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, the leaders of the Congress reached a compromise in the dispute over the rescue package totaling 700 billion dollars, which has been going on for days.
We have made serious progress - said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic President of the US House of Representatives, who said that all that remains is to put the agreement on paper.
The compromise reached on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Speaking about the outcome of the compromise, Finance Minister Henry Paulson stated: the program will work and be effective, but more needs to be done. According to Pelosi, this is not about saving Wall Street, but turning the economy around.
The written version of the package was made public before the opening of the Asian markets at 8:00 p.m. Washington time on Sunday (that is, 2:00 a.m. Monday, Central European time), but it did not cause a spectacular rise in the stock market.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will first vote on the draft law on the program, called the 2008 Economic Emergency Stabilization Act, and then it will be the turn of the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke with Pelosi on Saturday night, and news of the agreement was welcomed at the White House.
&quot;We are pleased with the progress made tonight and appreciate the bipartisan efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,&quot; White House spokesman Tony Fratto said.
By the way, the program differs from the original proposal of the Bush administration, which would have said that the 700 billion dollars would have been spent one at a time on the purchase of low-quality securities with a credit background.
Now, in the first round, no more than half of the 700 billion can be spent, so that 250 billion will be used immediately after the Congress is expected to vote on the matter on Monday, of which the Ministry of Finance will buy bad credit-backed securities, and the fate of another 100 billion dollars depends on the president&#39;s decision.
The program will be monitored by a special board, which will include the chairman of the Federal Reserve.
Spending the other half of the 700 billion depends on another decision by Congress.
Under the law, the Treasury can use a combination of tactics: it can simultaneously buy bad loans, mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, as well as other types of &quot;toxic&quot; loans.
The purchase can be made in the framework of auctions or directly, the officials of the ministry said.
The legislation allows the affected companies to participate in an insurance program where the Ministry of Finance guarantees the assets of concern, for which the companies will pay a premium corresponding to the expected damages.
Henry Paulson said: the law provides the necessary means so that up to 700 billion dollars can reach the urgent needs of the American financial system, whether it is the widespread purchase of bad assets, their insurance, or the avoidance of systemic risk associated with the collapse of a large financial institution.
We will take the necessary steps to be ready to introduce the law as soon as it is signed, he added.
On the other hand, the heads of banks that are in trouble and awaiting state aid can count on the government to limit their withdrawal money - which is simply called a golden parachute in overseas slang.
Payments are limited only in certain cases, and the limits depend on the way in which the Ministry of Finance provides assistance.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry buys through an auction, an additional tax will be levied on the golden parachute, unless the defunct bank manager is retired.
When outright buying bad loans, the government will step in aggressively to ensure that executive funds are not overstated.
Adding to the picture is that existing golden parachute contracts will not change, the restriction will only apply to new ones to still encourage participation in the program.
This is the first case in American history that there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of CEOs - commented the chairman of the committee responsible for financial services of the House of Representatives, Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the state acquires the right to acquire a stake in the banks participating in the program, so the risk for taxpayers is reduced, since they can ultimately win on the deal, as soon as the economy and the rescued bank get back on their feet.
The draft law states that in the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress, which stipulates how the expected losses from the financial sector can be returned to taxpayers.
Of course, there were those on both sides who expressed their doubts about the plan.
This is not what the American citizens asked us to do, i.e. it does not protect the taxpayers&#39; dollars, said California Republican Representative Darrell Issa.
His fellow Democrat from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believed that the measures were pushed by the same people who were responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to grow
In August 2008, the domestic sales prices of the industry rose by 0.1 percent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 - KSH reports.
The prices of industrial export sales were 1.1 percent higher compared to July 2008, and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of the change in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices were 0.7 percent higher than the previous month and 3.2 percent higher than a year earlier.
Compared to the previous month, the domestic sales prices of the industry increased only minimally, by 0.1 percent.
The domestic sales prices of the manufacturing sectors also rose slightly, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
In August 2008, the largest price increase occurred in the leather product and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), mainly due to the 4.6 percent monthly price increase of bags and belts and the 2.5 percent monthly price increase of footwear manufacturing.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in the prices of the chemical material and product manufacturing sector (1.6 percent).
Price reductions occurred in the petroleum processing (1.4 percent), electrical machine and instrument manufacturing (0.9 percent), and - to a minimal extent - wood processing (0.1 percent) sectors.
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities did not change.
In the other manufacturing sectors, we measured a price increase of between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector, which represents a significant weight in the industry&#39;s domestic sales, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, primarily as a result of the lingering effect of the official gas price increase implemented from July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison - with regard to the domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - prices increased the most in the petroleum processing sector (32.4 percent).
A 13.2 percent price increase was observed in the manufacturing sector of metal processing products, and an 11 percent increase in the production of food, beverages, and tobacco, which represents the decisive weight.
Price reductions occurred in the manufacturing of textiles and textile goods (2.5 percent), as well as the manufacturing of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price increase was between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices have increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
The prices of the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sector were 18.7 percent higher than a year earlier.
In domestic sales, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was seen in the sectors producing capital goods in August.
They increased by 0.3 percent in the sectors producing consumer goods, and prices in the sectors producing energy and further use did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase was observed in the energy and further consumption sectors (16.8 percent).
We measured a price increase of 6.8 percent in sectors producing consumer goods, and a 1.4 percent price decrease in investment goods.
The industry&#39;s export sales prices, measured in forints, rose by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, and fell by 3.9 percent in a 12-month comparison.
In one month, our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro and 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
