Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
The European Equal Opportunities Summit started today in Paris, which this year is hosted by France, which holds the EU presidency.
Lívia Járóka, the Fidesz representative of the European People&#39;s Party, as one of the main speakers of the professional conference, drew attention to educational segregation in her message to the plenum, because it is one of the most serious violations of the law affecting Roma children and, moreover, it is also the most serious obstacle to their empowerment.
The high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister of Employment and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Employment, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
Those invited to the meeting included representatives of governments, European social partners and the most important European rights defenders and civil society organizations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the Fidesz EP representative group, Járóka warned that in addition to discrimination in hiring, Roma are excluded from the labor market primarily due to their low level of education.
&quot;The vast majority of young Roma do not have a secondary education, and due to the poor quality of primary education, only an insignificant part of them can obtain a higher education&quot;.
Járóka further emphasized that, as a fundamental human right, education has a key role in the enforcement of other human rights.
Investing in the early education of Roma children can strengthen the economy of the European Union member states.
According to the representative, it is necessary to make the widest possible awareness of these connections - both among Roma and non-Roma.
Because the earlier the Roma student starts school, the more chances he has to become productive members of the labor market; they contribute to the national budget through taxes paid on income and consumption.
&quot;The Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education by virtue of their European Union citizenship, and the elimination of their low-quality and segregated education must be guaranteed,&quot; emphasized Lívia Járóka.
According to the representative, the goal and action-oriented cooperation of the European Union is necessary for the immediate acceleration of school desegregation processes, for which the correct enforcement of the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is essential.
&quot;The vicious cycle of poverty, segregation, and unemployment must be broken, Roma children must be given the opportunities provided by the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-fledged citizens,&quot; demanded Járóka.
In the spirit of the &quot;European Year of Equal Opportunities&quot; for everyone, the European Equality Summit, which has been held annually since last year&#39;s meeting in Berlin, aims to provide a unique forum for promoting the goals of equal opportunities and non-discrimination set at the European and Member State level.
Fox in the henhouse
In America, life and health insurers often refuse to sign an insurance contract with an applicant based on people&#39;s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the market for data will become uncontrollable.
&quot;There is a data protection program that always requires the consent of the person concerned to use prescription data.
It has to be in independent hands, otherwise we leave the hen&#39;s chicken to the fox,&quot; the Washington Post quotes Richard Dicket, the developer of the drug prescription tracking program.
The insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damage dependent on the health condition of the applying client, and if they deem the risk too high, they do not take out insurance.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only after knowing the results of the examination.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the client&#39;s ID number, he easily obtains from the pharmacies what medicines the person has bought in the past year and a half, and from this the program itself infers what disease he suffers from and what his medical condition is.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it indicates that your blood fat level is practically unmanageably high, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which also determine a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do apart from the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
Among the disadvantages is that some drugs can be used for several purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is considered a significant risk-increasing factor from the point of view of business insurers, the former are not.
Separate companies were formed to retrieve and process the data, and they ask for the patient&#39;s consent before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
The authorities are now obliging them to do so, although no penalty has been imposed for their failure so far.
More recently, some companies are already processing the results of laboratory tests and linking them with drug consumption data, so they can provide an even more accurate picture of the patients&#39; health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and it will become more and more difficult to control the use in parallel.
There is a separate healthcare data protection law, but it only applies to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
The bill is before the congress, which gives the authorities control over companies specializing in the provision of data.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough: that is why he further developed his program, which would bind the transfer of data to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot refuse the consent, otherwise the insurers will not conclude a contract with him.
So, the hens are somehow dependent on the fox&#39;s kindness.
