Opposition to Lukashenko: 110-0
Not a single opposition member made it into the Belarusian parliament following Sunday&#39;s elections.
According to Russian observers, this can be explained by the prosperity and stability ensured in the country led by Alexander Lukashenko, but according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), it can be explained by illegalities committed during the vote counting.
The OSCE, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, did not recognize the elections.
Although the 100-member legislature of the country of 10 million has been without an opposition for more than a decade, before yesterday&#39;s elections the opposition united under the name United Democratic Forces (ODSZ) seriously hoped that, following the constitutional amendment, Lukashenko, who renewed his presidential mandate for the fourth time in the disputed elections of 2006, would this time &quot;allows&quot; some opposition members to appear in parliament.
The ODSZ thus abandoned the previously considered boycott.
The opposition&#39;s expectations were based on the fact that Belarus, which is economically increasingly dependent on Russia - which took out a loan to reduce the ever-increasing price of Russian natural gas imports and also contributed to the transfer of Beltransgaz, which owns the gas pipelines passing through the country, into Russian hands - wanted to improve its relations with the EU, where the due to the Belarusian political system classified as anti-democratic, Lukashenko and several high-ranking politicians do not receive entry permits.
The fact that the OSCE, when evaluating the election campaign, emphasized the positive developments rather than the shortcomings - for example, the banning of a third of the opposition candidates from running - indicated a preliminary relief.
However, the OSCE&#39;s quick report on Monday already objected to the campaign - during which the opposition candidates were essentially not allowed to appear in the press - and especially to the fact that the opposition could not be present during the counting of votes.
At the same time, according to the opposition, there is still a noticeable improvement in the political system: political prisoners have been released, and Minsk is willing to have a minor confrontation with Moscow, still refusing to recognize South Ossetia and Abkhazia, which broke away from Georgia, even though Russia - with which Belarus forms a federal state on paper - has been considering the two areas as independent for a month now.
- We took two steps forward, one step back, but the most important thing is that the dialogue between Belarus and the EU has started - Aleksandr Milinkevich told our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate of the 2006 presidential election, it is desirable that this should remain, despite the fact that the &quot;power is afraid of allowing even one opposition member into the weightless parliament&quot;.
The opposition is not planning any protest actions after seeing the results, rather it is trying to convey its message about the need for economic reforms to the voters.
- Of course, we have a lot of problems with this, we have to print the opposition papers in Russia, the local authorities put obstacles in the way of distribution, but I still see that more and more people are supporting the change, also among the elderly - said Milinkevich, referring to the fact that Lukashenko&#39;s regime, which sees the creation of social security as its main result, is not considered adequate even by the most officially supported pensioners.
- Due to the country&#39;s indebtedness and the increase in the trade deficit, it is only a matter of time before the &quot;cemetery-like&quot; social security breaks down - Milinkevics believed.
Against the opposition politician, Russian observers described the elections as democratic.
Sergey Lebeyev, head of the mission of the Commonwealth of Independent States, told the Russian news agency Ria Novosti: &quot;people believe not in words, but in deeds&quot;, so the lack of opposition is nothing more than proof of the maturity of the Belarusian electorate.
