&quot;The expert opinion reveals that 5-10 percent of those who listen to their portable music player at high volume for more than an hour a day for five years can suffer permanent hearing loss,&quot; reads the explanation.
&quot;It is worrying that young people who use portable music players and mobile phones at high volumes and frequently are not aware that they can irreversibly damage their hearing,&quot; said Meglena Kuneva.
&quot;Scientific surveys indicate an indisputable risk, to which we must respond urgently,&quot; added the EU Commissioner.
The most important task is to inform consumers and widely distribute related information.
In the light of the mentioned expert opinion, we must also review the already existing control systems so that they can operate with sufficient efficiency and keep up with the latest technologies&quot;.
Brussels asked the independent scientific committee to investigate the problem, given the prevalence of portable music players and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they cause.
&quot;Researchers confirm that there is cause for concern. And the European Commission, in cooperation with member states and interested parties, is ready to examine what possible measures could be introduced to protect children and adolescents exposed to noise pollution caused by portable players and similar devices,&quot; he concluded. committee member.
The currently valid European safety regulation defines the maximum noise level that can be emitted by portable music players at 100 dB, however, there is growing concern about hearing damage resulting from the excessive use of such sound sources.
However, there are solutions such as reducing the level and duration of noise exposure, through which the aforementioned hearing impairments can be significantly reduced.
In its expert opinion, the EU&#39;s scientific committee explains that for users of portable playback devices who listen to music at high volume (more than 89 decibels) for five hours a week, the noise exposure exceeds the currently valid maximum value for workplace noise.
If someone listens to music under similar conditions for a long time, there is a risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This affects approximately 5-10 percent of portable device users, which may mean 2.5-10 million people in the EU.
