The elite are in danger
The phenomenon was already felt a few days ago, when the House of Representatives did not vote on the 700 billion dollar bailout package presented by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is supported by yesterday&#39;s New York Times, which informs that the current crisis has created a rift within the Republican Party, which is increasingly divided between the traditional, restrained, pro-federal institutions and business circles on the East Coast and the central and between a growing new direction in the southern states, against Washington and the financial world.
This trend manifested itself in a critical way during the House of Representatives vote mentioned in the introduction.
However, the above event is only one of the significant changes that the economic restructuring that is still taking place predicts or makes visible, and not only in the United States, but in the entire Western world, and perhaps even beyond.
It seems that the crisis, both in the USA and in Europe, only accelerates those phenomena that have been lurking for quite some time, which are consolidating in this new atmosphere and finally coming to light.
The first such phenomenon is re-actualization, the bringing back of the double category of state sovereignty to public consciousness, in connection with a kind of re-nationalization of the economy.
Indeed, the crisis affects those banking and financial institutions that maintain close relations with foreign countries, but primarily, and quite extensively, carry with them people and families who live in one country, one state.
This, on the other hand, means a direct political difficulty for those in government: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of those people who are also voters.
So, although the crisis appears to be worldwide in the economic sense, it is almost exclusively national in the political sense.
It seems that political internationalism is essentially stuck outside the coastline: the European Union is a clear proof of this, which, maneuvering between different interests and different national strategies, is unable to designate a unified political direction.
Therefore, everyone expects from the individual national governments the intervention, the rescue package, the revival and the new rules, but above all the opening of the monetary funds: because in a difficult situation only the individual states have economic resources, a financial stock that can be able to put things in order do things.
They have both the tools and the authority to use them: under the circumstances, they have two invaluable resources that no other market and no international organization will likely ever possess to such an extent.
On the other hand, the new emphasis placed on the nation-state by the crisis is fully consistent with the fact that the economic growth that has taken place in recent times is giving increasing importance to a factor that is closely related to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, while we were convinced that we had already entered the abstract world of the network, of increasingly sophisticated technology, and were convinced that the global financial world was destined to rule the world, we suddenly had to realize that the our future depends more and more on things, not the least abstract, like water, crops and petroleum.
From things that can be transported from one side of the planet to the other, they can still be completely tied to a defined place, an area.
So whoever dominates the area has a lot more trump cards than someone who was unfortunately born in a place with no crops, no oil and no water.
With that, I would also move on to the second innovation, which hints at a kind of fault line.
Anyone who says territory, state, government necessarily also says: politics, in other words leadership.
From this point of view, it seems that the economic crisis produces two overlapping phenomena:
On the one hand, the objective recognition of the need for authentic leadership, for people who can take control of events.
On the other hand, it brings a complete loss of credit to the current leadership, especially the economic leaders, who have proven to be completely incompetent and have proven that there are still many murky areas ahead of them.
Together, the two have an even deeper significance and, in a sense, more disturbing: the sense of discredit, impatience, inadequacy and isolation that affects the entire leadership elite in more and more Western countries.
So it seems that the belief that the time of the social elite, which has been at the top until now, is over, is spreading among an increasingly wide range of the population. It expired even before they had embraced their actions, experiences, lifestyle, culture, in the complex sense of the word. With this, the social elite is becoming more and more alienated from the opinion of the majority.
In short, the need for leadership, in a covert form, feeds a widespread but strong delegitimization movement against the ruling class and the traditional political system. This manifests itself in the unexpected &quot;riots&quot; of voters or, in recent times, sudden changes in the public mood. Examples include the coming to power of the conservatives in Austria and Bavaria, the collapse of the labor party unity in Great Britain, or the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and perhaps the victory of the Italian right wing can also be classified here).
It seems that the traditional elite, with its parties, programs, and we could even say that together with its habits, press and renowned intellectuals, understands less and less, and is therefore less and less able to represent what has been going on in the deeper layers of Western society for some time. Furthermore, the economic crisis is getting stronger, spreading, and is potentially able to create more and more intemperate tempers.
Despite all this, to speak of an &quot;imminent revolt of the masses&quot; would frankly be an exaggeration.
But keeping your eyes open doesn&#39;t hurt at all.
