Medicines? No fruit juice!
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These thirst-quenching drinks with a high vitamin content, popular especially in the summer, if they enter the body together with certain life-saving drugs, change their absorption, increasing or reducing their effect depending on the case. This can have serious health consequences.
David Bailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, drew attention to the risks of using canned or fresh fruit juices together with certain medications. The professor announced at the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia: a glass of grapefruit, orange or apple juice can reduce the absorption of certain life-saving drugs, thereby preventing their beneficial effects and endangering the patient&#39;s health.
Grapefruit juice has already been in the dock when it was found that it can increase the effect of some antibiotics, antihistamines, anti-anxiety drugs, heart rhythm regulators and nerve drugs to a level that can be considered toxic.
DANGEROUS DRUGS - Two years ago, the Italian Institute of Pharmacy itself disclosed the news in its official gazette, and at the same time warned doctors and patients to take seriously the risks associated with the aforementioned co-consumption and to be careful what they drink when taking drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT ONLY GRAPEFRUIT - According to researchers, orange and apple juice also contain substances that inhibit the effectiveness of medicines.
The list of active ingredients whose absorption is hindered by grapefruit and other fruit juices could be long.
This is what Michele Carruba, a professor at the Department of Pharmacy at the State University of Milan, points out: &quot;Discoveries of this kind are usually reported immediately to the various national and international pharmaceutical institutes, who, if necessary, make sure to change the data on the information sheet of the given drug.
That&#39;s why you should always read the information sheet of the medicine you intend to take, and if something is not clear, don&#39;t let yourself be influenced, but ask your doctor or pharmacist clearly,&quot; emphasized the specialist of the Ansa institute.
