Students suffer from expensive rental fees, a room can cost up to 900 euros
The market for accommodation for university students is not affected by the crisis.
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the Tenants&#39; Union, a student can pay up to 900 euros for a single room in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples and 600 in Rome.
&quot;The phenomenon has now reached such amazing proportions that - due to the huge total costs falling on families - large sections of students are excluded from the opportunity to learn,&quot; explains Laura Mariani, head of Sunia&#39;s study office. &quot;The high demand from students in these cities has distorted the market to such an extent that a general process of price increases has started for local residents as well.&quot;
In the majority of cases, the real estate offers also contain a series of irregularities: unregistered contracts without rent restrictions, with linked subleases.
According to Sunia, an extraordinary measure would be needed that would create an opportunity to maximize prices through the revision of the taxation system.
The details of the survey reveal that 450 euros are asked for a bed in the Brianza area of Milan; the price of a single room ranges from 650 euros (Bande Nere area) to an average of 800 euros (Lambiate, Udine and Fiera), but can reach 900 euros (Vittoria area).
In Florence, a bed costs on average 350/400 euros, a room about 700.
In Bologna, where the majority of students live in the area close to the university, a bed costs 250/280 euros for a double room and 370-500 euros for a single room.
In Rome, in areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) they charge around 600 euros for a bed in a single room and 450 for a double room.
Prices are slightly cheaper (€550 for a single room) around the other universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can save a bit in the suburbs: a bed costs 300 euros and a single room costs 450 in Prenestina, Centocelle and other similar districts.
In Naples, they ask for 300/450 euros for a bed, from 400 to 600 euros for a room. Prices are highest around Policlinico, Vomero and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, you have to pay 250/350 euros for a bed, and at least 350 for a single room.
In smaller cities, the prices are lower in absolute terms, but they represent a greater weight within the city budget.
In cities such as Perugia, where students from outside the EU often look for accommodation, another anomaly can be seen: the rent charged to foreign students is about 25-30 percent higher than that of Italian tenants.
Goodbye good old Cinema Paradiso, the days of the old cinemas in the cities are over
Traditional cinemas are closing in favor of multiplexes.
&quot;A city without cinemas is a blind city, like a face without eyes&quot;.
The pictures made by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively present everything that takes place in the Italian cities, but also in the rural regions.
The displacement of cinemas - the emergence of large, multi-screen cinemas in the suburbs, and the consequent decline of single-screen cinemas in city centers - is a seemingly inevitable and irreversible process, but at the same time it bears all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
When places full of history and memories disappear, &quot;it&#39;s like losing a friend, an acquaintance with whom we shared our journey and many experiences,&quot; says the director of Cinema Paradiso. The film, which twenty years ago won Tornatore an Oscar and the grand prize of the Cannes festival, tells the lyrical story of a small-town cinema, the yearning for a cinema experience that may have been lost forever.
The data provided by Anec, the largest association of operators, speaks clearly: 316 traditional movie theaters have closed in the last five years. Cinemas in big cities recorded the biggest losses: 10 movie theaters closed in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
The most affected regions are Emilia-Romagna, which lost 82 single-screen cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And that the rise of multiplexes is responsible for their disappearance, there is nothing better than the fact that the number of newly opened multiplex cinemas is the highest in these three regions of Italy: in the last five years, the number of theaters has increased by 195 in Lombardy, by 81 in Tuscany and by the same amount in Emilia - In Romagna.
&quot;The number of units in Italy has increased irrationally,&quot; says Anec president Paolo Protti. &quot;It&#39;s okay to build new facilities, but the survival of the existing ones should also be ensured, because when a city cinema closes, not all passers-by are willing to go to the multiplexes.
Not to mention the unused financial funds intended to support the operators: the state&#39;s overdue debt can be estimated at around 10 million euros.
From an ethical and moral point of view, it is shameful that the government does not comply with the existing legislation.
16-18 million euros per year would be needed to maintain the market&quot;.
The case of Bologna deserves special attention. It is the first Italian city that, in its concern over closures, has decided to remedy the problem through an agreement between the municipality and Anec, in order to protect and boost single-screen cinemas in the outer and inner city.
Provisions would include tax incentives for operators, as well as benefits for the public to promote accessibility: spectators can drive into restricted areas and park at reduced rates in certain parking lots.
&quot;I like this initiative,&quot; says Giuseppe Tornatore, &quot;and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna&#39;s example, even by introducing other measures.
But it is also certain that traditional cinemas, in order to be able to fight the dominance of multiplexes, have to improve the sound and picture quality, because today&#39;s audience is much more demanding.
The preservation of traditional cinema has always been an important issue for me: the closing of the Supercinema in Bagheria - where I spent my childhood and youth - gave me the spark that finally made me make Cinema Paradiso, even though I had been thinking about it for 10 years.
I&#39;ve lived in Rome for 25 years, so when I walk past the closed Rialto or the Quirinale on via Nazionale, I turn my head away to avoid seeing the dust-blackened posters. I had so many experiences here&quot;
