Energy comes from waves, and now the big ones are coming
An inexhaustible source of energy that covers 70 percent of the planet&#39;s surface and is only now being discovered by major international energy companies
Waves, sea currents, tides are all sources of renewable energy that giants like Chevron have set their eyes on, and are now trying to get their hands on it.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been researched for a hundred years. In the 1970s, during the first oil crisis, research intensified.
Around 1980, when the price of crude oil fell, the idea of harnessing marine energy was shelved, but today the demands of environmental protection and the renewed rise in the price of crude oil are giving new impetus to the sector.
According to a 2007 estimate by the London-based World Energy Council (WEC), 15 percent of the world&#39;s electricity needs could be covered by facilities utilizing the waves of the seas.
This amount is twice what is currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be currents and tides.
The giants are on the move.
Enersis was the first company to commit to marine energy, signing an agreement in 2005 for a power plant in northern Portugal.
It seemed like a revolutionary move when the signing was announced.
Two years have passed since then, and more and more companies are voting in favor of marine energy, including those who were committed supporters of traditional energy until now.
&quot;Chevron is studying technologies that utilize ocean energy and is considering the possibility of working with us,&quot; a spokesperson for one of the American oil industry giant&#39;s affiliates told the Wall Street Journal.
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of the license issued by the US Energy Commission for the start-up of a marine energy project in Alaska.
The matter is of no small importance, especially if we take into account that the USA is currently extracting crude oil in Alaska, and even President Bush recently launched a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron, New York&#39;s Verdant Power Inc. and New Jersey&#39;s Ocean Power are also following the path of energy extracted from the sea. The amounts invested so far, as far as the details are known, testify to growing interest.
The technology is waiting to be developed.
According to the experts, it is still a rudimentary technology, if only because the energy that can be obtained from the sea does not dispel doubts about the environmental impact.
The facilities that currently exist, similar to those in Portugal or Scotland, are all small in size and therefore do not cause too much of a problem in terms of the ecosystem.
On the other hand, in order to produce energy on a larger scale, facilities with a greater environmental impact are needed.
There are several options: Ocean Power, for example, uses an interconnected buoy system.
The shocks created by the waves and which move the buoys up and down are converted into hydraulic pressure by the pistons and cylinders located in them.
The pressure turns a turbine, which in turn powers a generator.
Electricity reaches the land via cables running under the sea.
There are currently four facilities of a similar nature in the planning stage, which are only awaiting federal approval. Some of the energy produced would be used in a military installation.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, has already started generating energy for a shopping center and a parking lot with the help of six subsea turbines located in New York&#39;s East River Strait.
At high tide, the movement of the water turns the blades of the turbines, and this turning motion powers the generator.
Verdant said it has a long list of partners waiting for permits just to use the energy.
Tide after wave.
Currently, the opportunities that can be exploited through the tides deserve special attention.
Although it is a periodic phenomenon, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and therefore can be considered a more reliable source of energy.
New York, Maine and Alaska, along with other coastal states, spent $7.5 million in 2008 just to harness the energy provided by the tides. This amount is expected to increase to 35 million in 2009.
